export const ADVANCED_FIQH_QA = [
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_1',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the doctrine of Fiqh Al-Muwazanat (jurisprudence of balancing) developed by Imam Ibn Taymiyyah, and how does it resolve the tension between Maslahah and Mafsadah in contemporary Islamic legal decisions?',
    answer: 'Ibn Taymiyyah\'s Fiqh Al-Muwazanat (jurisprudence of balancing competing interests) is articulated across his Majmoo\' Al-Fatawa and Dar\' Ta\'arud Al-Aql wa An-Naql. His core thesis is that Islamic law is fundamentally teleological — every ruling serves a purpose (maqsad), and when purposes compete, the jurist must weigh them through a principled hierarchy rather than mechanical application of isolated rules. The doctrine operates on several levels. First, Ibn Taymiyyah distinguishes between certain mafsadah and probable maslahah — certain harm cannot be incurred for probable benefit (Al-Mafsadah Al-Mutahaqqaqah la tuzal bil-Maslahah Al-Mutawahhimah). Second, he develops the principle that greater harms may be incurred to prevent graver harms (Ad-Darar Al-Akbar yuzal bid-Darar Al-Askar) — a refinement of the classical principle that distinguishes his jurisprudence from rigid application. Third, his analysis of collective vs. individual interests: the communal maslahah (maslahah \'ammah) outweighs individual interest (maslahah khassah) in cases of genuine conflict, but this cannot be used to systematically destroy individual rights in the name of collective benefit. Fourth — and most sophisticated — his doctrine addresses what he calls Tafwit Al-Maslahah: deliberately allowing a benefit to be lost is sometimes preferable to actively incurring harm in pursuit of it, because action carries moral weight that inaction does not. Contemporary applications: scholars deploy this framework in bioethics (organ donation when death is certain vs. statistical benefit to recipients), in Islamic finance (distinguishing between hiyal that formally avoid riba vs. genuinely riba-free structures), and in political jurisprudence (when to cooperate with non-Islamic governance structures). Ibn Al-Qayyim extends this in I\'lam Al-Muwaqqi\'in with his famous statement: "The Shariah is built entirely on wisdom and human welfare in this life and the next — it is all justice, mercy, benefit, and wisdom."',
    source: 'Majmoo\' Al-Fatawa, Ibn Taymiyyah; I\'lam Al-Muwaqqi\'in, Ibn Al-Qayyim; Al-Muwafaqat, Ash-Shatibi; Qa\'idah fi Al-Masalih wa Al-Mafasid, Ibn Taymiyyah',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_2',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Explain Imam Ash-Shatibi\'s tripartite classification of Maqasid (Daruriyyat, Hajiyyat, Tahsiniyyat) and his theory of kulliyyat al-millah — how does the totality of particular rulings establish universal principles?',
    answer: 'Ash-Shatibi\'s contribution in Al-Muwafaqat represents the most sophisticated development of Maqasid theory before the modern period. His tripartite classification is well known: Daruriyyat (essentials without which human life collapses — religion, life, intellect, lineage, wealth), Hajiyyat (needs whose absence creates severe hardship without threatening existence — rukhsah, ease provisions), and Tahsiniyyat (enhancements that improve life without being essential — good manners, hygiene, aesthetic refinement). What is less studied is his theory of kulliyyat al-millah and his istiqra\' methodology. Ash-Shatibi argues that the universal principles of Islamic law cannot be established from any single text — they emerge from inductive examination (istiqra\') of the totality of particular rulings across all chapters of fiqh. When a principle appears consistently across multiple independent textual sources, its universality is established with a degree of certainty that no single text could provide. This is his epistemological revolution: qat\'i universals derived from the cumulative convergence of zanni particulars. His kulliyyat al-millah (universal principles of the community) operate at a higher level than individual rulings — they are the axioms of Islamic law. No particular ruling, however apparently supported by a specific text, can violate a universal principle without the jurist having made an error somewhere. The most radical application: if a ruling derived by apparently valid ijtihad produces a result that consistently violates a maqsad across multiple cases, the derivation is wrong regardless of its apparent textual validity. This places Maqasid not as a supplement to usul but as a check on it. Ibn Ashur develops this further in Maqasid Ash-Shariah Al-Islamiyyah, arguing that preservation of social order (nizam al-ummah) and universality of justice (shumul al-adalah) are primary maqasid not adequately identified by Al-Ghazali.',
    source: 'Al-Muwafaqat, Ash-Shatibi (Vol. 1-2 especially); Maqasid Ash-Shariah Al-Islamiyyah, Ibn Ashur; Al-Mustasfa, Al-Ghazali; Dirasat fi Falsafat Usul Al-Fiqh, Ahmad Ar-Raysouni',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_3',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the classical debate on Ta\'lil Al-Ahkam (rational causation of legal rulings) between the Ash\'ari-Mu\'tazili divide, and how does Imam Al-Ghazali\'s position in Al-Mustasfa differ from Ibn Hazm\'s Zahiri rejection of all qiyas?',
    answer: 'The debate on Ta\'lil Al-Ahkam — whether legal rulings have discernible rational causes (\'ilal) that can be identified and extended — is among the deepest in Islamic legal philosophy. The Mu\'tazilah held that reason could independently determine the goodness or badness of actions (husn wa qubh \'aqliyan), making ta\'lil the very foundation of ethics. The Ash\'ariyyah rejected this: Allah\'s command alone determines goodness and badness (husn wa qubh shar\'iyan). The practical consequence: if rulings have no rational \'illah, qiyas is impossible, because there is nothing to extend. Ibn Hazm Al-Andalusi in Al-Ihkam fi Usul Al-Ahkam took the logical Zahiri conclusion: qiyas is haram, the \'illah concept is a human invention, and only explicit texts (zahir) apply. Every unstated case is either mubah by default or must be resolved by direct analogy from the closest explicit text — but that analogy cannot be based on a shared rational cause. Al-Ghazali\'s position in Al-Mustasfa is the most sophisticated Ash\'ari response. He accepts that rulings serve purposes (Al-Ghazali\'s own contribution to Maqasid) without conceding that those purposes are rationally necessary. Allah could have legislated otherwise; He happened to legislate in ways that serve human welfare, but the binding force of rulings comes from command, not from wisdom. The \'illah in qiyas is not a rational cause but an indicator (amarah, dalil) that the lawgiver intended the ruling to apply where the indicator exists — this is the crucial distinction. Imam Al-Amidi in Al-Ihkam provides the fullest classical response to the Zahiri position, demonstrating through textual analysis that the Prophet ﷺ himself explicitly cited rationales for rulings, extended rulings by analogy, and accepted the Companions\' analogical reasoning — establishing that ta\'lil and qiyas are themselves Sunnah-based, not rationalist innovations.',
    source: 'Al-Mustasfa, Al-Ghazali; Al-Ihkam fi Usul Al-Ahkam, Ibn Hazm; Al-Ihkam fi Usul Al-Ahkam, Al-Amidi; Al-Wajiz, Al-Ghazali; Husn Al-\'Aqida, various',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_4',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Analyze the doctrine of Siyasah Shar\'iyyah as developed by Ibn Taymiyyah in As-Siyasah Ash-Shar\'iyyah fi Islah Ar-Ra\'i wa Ar-Ra\'iyyah — what are its foundations, its relationship to fiqh, and why did Ibn Taymiyyah consider it obligatory rather than merely permissible?',
    answer: 'Ibn Taymiyyah\'s As-Siyasah Ash-Shar\'iyyah is a treatise on the Islamic theory of governance that fundamentally recasts the relationship between revealed fiqh and political administration. His opening thesis is stark: "The obligation of commanding good and forbidding evil, and the establishment of justice by the ruler, is among the greatest obligations of the religion and the greatest benefits of the nation." The traditional view treated Siyasah (administrative policy) as what rulers do within the space left by Shariah — permissible within limits but secondary to fiqh. Ibn Taymiyyah inverts this. Siyasah Shar\'iyyah is not what rulers do beyond fiqh — it is itself fiqh, specifically the fiqh of public governance and collective obligations. His argument proceeds in three stages. First, he establishes that justice (\'adl) is the supreme objective of governance, citing the famous hadith of Mu\'adh about judging by reason when no text applies — this establishes that the maqasid of justice extends beyond specific textual provisions. Second, he demonstrates that many specific rulings depend entirely on the imam\'s implementation — hudud, zakah collection, defensive jihad, protection of public interests — without which the entire fiqh structure is hollow. Third, his most controversial claim: a just non-Muslim ruler is preferable to an unjust Muslim ruler from the perspective of God\'s purposes in creation, because God\'s maqsad is justice, not merely formal compliance with Islamic identity. This has implications for how Muslim minorities engage with non-Muslim governance. Ibn Al-Qayyim extends this in At-Turuq Al-Hukmiyyah with the doctrine that any policy achieving justice — even without a specific textual precedent — falls within Siyasah Shar\'iyyah, because "Allah has made clear that His purpose is the establishment of justice and equity among people, so whatever path leads to justice and equity is part of the religion and contradicts nothing in it."',
    source: 'As-Siyasah Ash-Shar\'iyyah, Ibn Taymiyyah; At-Turuq Al-Hukmiyyah, Ibn Al-Qayyim; Al-Ahkam As-Sultaniyyah, Al-Mawardi; Al-Ahkam As-Sultaniyyah, Abu Ya\'la; Majmoo\' Al-Fatawa (Vol. 28), Ibn Taymiyyah',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_5',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the doctrine of Al-Masalih Al-Mursalah in Imam Malik\'s jurisprudence and how does it differ from the Maslahah concept in Al-Ghazali and Ash-Shatibi? Trace the development through Imam Ash-Shatibi\'s critique of "unrestricted maslahah."',
    answer: 'The concept of Al-Masalih Al-Mursalah (unrestricted/unattested public interests) originates in Maliki jurisprudence and represents the most contested secondary source in Islamic legal theory. The classical Maliki position, attributed to Imam Malik himself and systematized by Ash-Shatibi, holds that the Shariah has established a general objective of serving human welfare, and that any measure genuinely serving that welfare — even without a specific textual basis — may serve as a legal argument if it does not contradict any established text and falls within the recognized categories of human welfare (din, nafs, nasl, \'aql, mal). The critical qualification: the maslahah must be genuine, certain, and universal — not speculative, private, or merely convenient. Al-Ghazali in Al-Mustasfa strongly restricts Maslahah Mursalah: he accepts it only when the interest is Daruri (essential), Qat\'iyyah (certain), Kulliyyah (universal), and compatible with the spirit of the Shariah. He explicitly rejects using unrestricted maslahah in matters affecting individual rights or in cases where a specific text points in another direction. Ash-Shatibi\'s critique of what he calls Al-Masalih Al-Mursalah Al-Mutawahhimah (imaginary unrestricted interests) is the most important classical warning against its abuse. He argues that most claimed applications of unrestricted maslahah are either: (a) not genuine masalih but rather individual or collective desires disguised as welfare arguments; (b) already covered by existing textual principles and therefore not truly "unrestricted"; or (c) opposed to established textual principles and therefore categorically invalid. His rule: "Every maslahah that conflicts with a textual principle is either invalid (fasidah) or the jurist has erred in identifying it as genuine." The modern relevance: contemporary scholars who invoke unrestricted maslahah to justify major reforms (equal inheritance, decriminalization of what the Quran prohibits) are precisely the case Ash-Shatibi warned against — masalih that directly contradict Quranic principles are not masalih at all, regardless of the sociological arguments marshaled in their favor.',
    source: 'Al-Muwafaqat (Vol. 2), Ash-Shatibi; Al-Mustasfa, Al-Ghazali; Shihab Ad-Din Al-Qarafi, Ash-Shuruq; Masalih Al-Mursalah, Muhammad Sa\'id Ramadan Al-Bouti; Al-Fiqh Al-Islami fi Tariq At-Tajdid, Al-Qaradawi',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_6',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Analyze the Hanafi doctrine of Istihsan as developed by Imam As-Sarakhsi in Al-Mabsut — distinguish its four types and explain how Imam Ash-Shafi\'i\'s rejection of Istihsan ("whoever uses Istihsan has legislated") is a mischaracterization of its legitimate forms.',
    answer: 'Imam As-Sarakhsi\'s treatment of Istihsan in Al-Mabsut and his dedicated Usul As-Sarakhsi represents the most systematic classical defense of the Hanafi doctrine. Istihsan literally means "to deem something good" — legally, it is departing from what qiyas (analogical reasoning) would indicate to a stronger ruling based on another textual indicator. As-Sarakhsi identifies four types: (1) Istihsan by Nass (specific text) — a Quranic verse or hadith establishes a ruling contrary to what general qiyas would produce. The hadith permitting salam contracts (forward sales) contradicts the qiyas principle that a sale must involve existent goods at the time of contract — the text overrides the analogy. (2) Istihsan by Ijma\' — scholarly consensus establishes a ruling contrary to qiyas. The permissibility of istisna\' (manufacturing contracts) and ijara (lease) contracts violates general qiyas but is established by consensus — therefore accepted. (3) Istihsan by Darurah (necessity) — genuine necessity overrides the analogical ruling. The Hanafi ruling that small amounts of unavoidable impurity (na\'jas) in water used for irrigation or industrial purposes is excused violates qiyas-based purity rules but is necessitated by \'umum al-balwa (widespread unavoidable circumstances). (4) Istihsan by Maslahah — public interest overrides qiyas when no specific text or consensus exists. This is the most controversial type, and As-Sarakhsi restricts it severely: the maslahah must be certain, general, and not merely speculative. Regarding Ash-Shafi\'i\'s famous rejection: his statement "man istahsana faqad sharra\'a" (whoever uses istihsan has legislated) is directed at arbitrary istihsan — subjective preference without any textual basis, which is indeed haram. Ash-Shafi\'i himself uses what the Hanafis would call Istihsan by Nass and Istihsan by Darurah — he simply does not call it that. The substantive disagreement is only over Istihsan by Maslahah, and even there the disagreement is about how rigorously the maslahah must be grounded in textual principles before overriding analogical reasoning.',
    source: 'Usul As-Sarakhsi (Vol. 2); Al-Mabsut, As-Sarakhsi; Ar-Risalah, Ash-Shafi\'i; Al-Mustasfa, Al-Ghazali; Fiqh Al-Istihsan, various',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_7',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the concept of Al-\'Uqud Al-Murakkabah (compound contracts) in contemporary Islamic finance jurisprudence — how do classical scholars distinguish permissible combination from prohibited Hiyal (legal stratagems), and what is the evidence from Ibn Al-Qayyim\'s analysis?',
    answer: 'The permissibility of Al-\'Uqud Al-Murakkabah (compound or combined contracts) is among the most contested questions in contemporary Islamic financial jurisprudence, with direct implications for Tawarruq (monetization), commodity murabahah, and structured Islamic banking products. The classical foundation: the hadith "Two sales in one sale (bay\'atayn fi bay\'ah) are prohibited" (Sunan At-Tirmidhi 1231, authenticated) is interpreted by different schools as prohibiting (a) two prices for a single good simultaneously, (b) a loan combined with a sale, or (c) two separate contracts linked as conditions of each other. The Hanbali position, developed through Ibn Taymiyyah and Ibn Al-Qayyim, draws the critical distinction between: (A) Contracts that are structurally combined — where the combination creates a new contract type with its own distinct legal consequences, and (B) Contracts that are merely sequentially linked for the purpose of achieving what a single prohibited contract would achieve. Ibn Al-Qayyim in I\'lam Al-Muwaqqi\'in develops the doctrine of Al-Hiyal Al-Mahzurah (prohibited legal stratagems) with extraordinary rigor: the test of a prohibited hilah is not whether it formally consists of individually permissible acts, but whether its purpose is to achieve a prohibited outcome and whether the parties have structured it specifically for that purpose. His famous criterion: "The ruling follows the maqsad (purpose) not merely the lafz (form)." Applied to modern finance: a commodity murabahah transaction where the bank purchases commodities it has no intention of holding, immediately sells them to the client, and the client immediately sells them back through a pre-arranged broker — with the net result being a cash loan at a predetermined return — is a hilah under Ibn Al-Qayyim\'s criterion, regardless of its formal three-contract structure. The Tawarruq Munazzam (organized tawarruq) is therefore prohibited by the OIC Fiqh Academy (Resolution 179, 2009) precisely on these grounds.',
    source: 'I\'lam Al-Muwaqqi\'in (Vol. 3-4), Ibn Al-Qayyim; Majmoo\' Al-Fatawa (Vol. 29), Ibn Taymiyyah; Al-\'Uqud Al-Murakkabah fi Al-Fiqh Al-Islami, Al-\'Imrani; OIC Fiqh Academy Resolution 179; Ma\'ayir Al-Hay\'ah Ash-Shar\'iyyah (AAOIFI Standards)',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_8',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Explain Imam An-Nawawi\'s methodology in Al-Majmu\' Sharh Al-Muhadhdhab — how does he distinguish between Mu\'tamad (authoritative) and Shadh (anomalous) opinions within the Shafi\'i school, and what criteria determine the tarjih (preference) of one position over another?',
    answer: 'Imam An-Nawawi\'s Al-Majmu\' Sharh Al-Muhadhdhab (his commentary on Al-Shirazi\'s Al-Muhadhdhab) is the most comprehensive work in the Shafi\'i school and represents the fullest expression of intra-madhab tarjih methodology. An-Nawawi came at a critical juncture in the Shafi\'i school when hundreds of years of doctrinal development had produced a complex body of opinions, with significant disagreements between Al-Mawardi, Al-Juwaini (Imam Al-Haramayn), Al-Ghazali, Ar-Rafi\'i, and others — all considered authoritative Shafi\'i scholars. An-Nawawi\'s criteria for tarjih (preference between competing Shafi\'i opinions) are systematic: (1) Proximity to the explicit texts of Imam Ash-Shafi\'i himself — An-Nawawi consistently checks opinions against Ash-Shafi\'i\'s Al-Umm and Al-Mukhtasar. (2) Strength of hadith evidence — An-Nawawi, as one of the greatest hadith scholars of his time, privileges opinions grounded in stronger hadith chains even when this requires departing from dominant Shafi\'i positions. (3) Consistency with Usul Ash-Shafi\'i (Shafi\'i legal principles) as articulated in Ar-Risalah. (4) The position of the majority of Shafi\'i scholars (jumhur Al-As-hab). (5) When these criteria conflict, An-Nawawi\'s personal ijtihad and the principle of rational consistency. His distinction between Mu\'tamad (authoritative — the position to be relied upon for fatwa) and Shadh (anomalous — reported from a Shafi\'i scholar but not to be acted upon) is crucial: a Shadh position may have a strong argument and may even correspond to the position of another madhab, but if it contradicts what An-Nawawi considers the authentic Shafi\'i methodology, it is shadh for the Shafi\'i jurist. His critical observation: "Many issues that Al-Ghazali declared consensus (ijma\') in Al-Wajiz and Al-Wasit are in fact disputed — the student of fiqh must not accept such claims without verification."',
    source: 'Al-Majmu\' Sharh Al-Muhadhdhab, An-Nawawi; Al-Majmu\' (Introduction by An-Nawawi on his methodology); Rawdat At-Talibin, An-Nawawi; Tashih At-Tanbih, An-Nawawi; Al-Minhaj, An-Nawawi',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_9',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the doctrine of Sadd Al-Dhara\'i\' in Maliki and Hanbali jurisprudence, and how does Ibn Al-Qayyim\'s treatment in I\'lam Al-Muwaqqi\'in extend it into a comprehensive theory of legal prevention that addresses modern issues like media regulation and financial instruments?',
    answer: 'Sadd Al-Dhara\'i\' (blocking the pathways to harm) is a legal principle most extensively developed in Maliki and Hanbali jurisprudence, though its roots are Prophetic. The foundational Quranic evidence: ﴿وَلَا تَسُبُّوا الَّذِينَ يَدْعُونَ مِن دُونِ اللَّهِ فَيَسُبُّوا اللَّهَ﴾ (Quran 6:108) — a permissible act (insulting idols) prohibited because it leads to a prohibited consequence (insulting Allah). The Prophetic evidence: the prohibition on gathering in numbers that could alarm people, the prohibition on looking into others\' houses without permission, and the prohibition on sitting on graves — all acts prohibited not for intrinsic harm but for what they lead to. Ibn Al-Qayyim in I\'lam Al-Muwaqqi\'in (Vol. 3, the section on Sadd Al-Dhara\'i\') provides the most comprehensive treatment. He argues that the principle has four levels of application based on the probability and severity of the harm: (1) Actions that invariably (in most cases) lead to harm — prohibited with the same force as the harm itself. (2) Actions that frequently (in many cases) lead to harm — prohibited unless a compelling counter-interest exists. (3) Actions that rarely lead to harm — not prohibited on the basis of Sadd Al-Dhara\'i\' alone, as this would create intolerable restriction. (4) Actions that are specifically designed to circumvent prohibitions — prohibited regardless of whether they actually cause harm in this instance. Ibn Al-Qayyim\'s extension into what we would call structural harm is radical: he argues that if a category of transactions or actions creates a systematic pattern of harm in society — even if each individual instance appears permissible — the category may be prohibited by Sadd Al-Dhara\'i\'. This is his basis for prohibiting many financial instruments: not each transaction as such, but the systemic pattern of wealth concentration and economic injustice they create. Applied to modern media: content that individually appears permissible (entertainment without explicit haram) but that patterns of consumption demonstrate leads reliably to harm (desensitization, weakening of religious commitment) falls under level (2) of Ibn Al-Qayyim\'s hierarchy.',
    source: 'I\'lam Al-Muwaqqi\'in (Vol. 3), Ibn Al-Qayyim; Al-Muwafaqat (Vol. 2), Ash-Shatibi; Al-Furuq, Al-Qarafi; Usul Al-Fiqh, Abu Zahrah; Sadd Al-Dhara\'i\' fi Ash-Shari\'ah Al-Islamiyyah, Ibn Bayyah',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_10',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Analyze the classical controversy over the permissibility of Taqlid Al-Madhhab for a qualified scholar — contrasting the views of Ibn Taymiyyah (who permits departure from one\'s madhab when evidence is clear), An-Nawawi (who requires consistency within the madhab), and the Maliki position on Taqlid Al-A\'lam.',
    answer: 'The question of whether a scholar with some degree of qualification must follow their madhab or may depart when evidence is clearer elsewhere is among the most practically significant controversies in Islamic legal methodology. Three major positions: (1) The dominant later position (mutaakhkhirun of all four schools): a qualified scholar follows their madhab unless they achieve the level of full ijtihad — which effectively no one achieves in the later period. This position was institutionalized for pedagogical and social reasons: consistency and predictability of legal rulings, accessibility for non-scholars, and prevention of the "shopping" for convenient opinions that Ibn Al-Qayyim criticizes. (2) Ibn Taymiyyah\'s position: a scholar who can evaluate evidence is obligated to follow the stronger evidence regardless of which madhab it leads to. Following a madhab against clear evidence is haram — the muqallid follows the madhab because he cannot evaluate evidence, but the scholar who can evaluate evidence is obligated to do so. His evidence: "There is no taqlid for one who knows the proof" (La taqlida li-man \'alima ad-dalil) — a methodological principle accepted by all schools in theory but applied differently. His critique is directed specifically at the practice of scholars finding loopholes within their madhab through weak internal opinions rather than following the clear external evidence of another madhab. (3) An-Nawawi\'s position: consistency within the madhab is required for the jurist issuing fatwas because departing from the madhab creates unpredictability and enables subjective selection. However, An-Nawawi himself in Al-Majmu\' repeatedly departs from the Shafi\'i position when hadith evidence clearly contradicts it — demonstrating that his position is institutional rather than fully principled. (4) The Maliki principle of Taqlid Al-A\'lam: when a mujtahid is uncertain, they must follow the most knowledgeable scholar available on that specific question — not their customary madhab authority. This principle, developed by Al-Qarafi in Ash-Shuruq, is the most nuanced position: madhab loyalty is a heuristic of convenience, not a theological obligation.',
    source: 'Majmoo\' Al-Fatawa (Vol. 20), Ibn Taymiyyah; Rawdat At-Talibin (Introduction), An-Nawawi; Ash-Shuruq, Al-Qarafi; Al-Insaf fi Bayan Asbab Al-Ikhtilaf, Ad-Dahlawi; Raf\' Al-Malam, Ibn Taymiyyah',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_11',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is Ibn Hazm Al-Andalusi\'s critique of Ijma\' in Al-Ihkam fi Usul Al-Ahkam, and how does his reconceptualization of consensus as "Ijma\' As-Sahabah" (consensus of the Companions alone) challenge the traditional four-sources structure of Islamic law?',
    answer: 'Ibn Hazm\'s treatment of Ijma\' in Al-Ihkam is the most sustained classical critique of the consensus principle and arguably the most logically rigorous position on its scope. His central argument: the traditional Ijma\' — agreement of all mujtahid scholars of any given era — is theoretically impossible to establish because (a) we cannot know who all the mujtahids of an era are, (b) we cannot verify that all of them agreed, (c) scholars in distant lands may have held different opinions never transmitted to us, and (d) as each new generation adds scholars, the composition of "the scholars" changes continuously. Therefore, the traditional Ijma\' cannot be a source of certainty. Ibn Hazm\'s counter-proposal: the only Ijma\' that can be established with certainty is the Ijma\' of the Companions (Sahabah), because their number was finite, their statements are preserved in the hadith literature, and the Prophet ﷺ explicitly testified to their authority. Anything the Companions agreed upon — and whose agreement is documented — has the force of Sunnah because they cannot have agreed on something the Prophet ﷺ would have rejected. Beyond this, what scholars call "Ijma\'" of later generations is either (a) correctly an Ijma\' of the Companions which later scholars merely preserved, or (b) a dominant position (mashhur) that should be treated as the opinion of its originators, no more. The implications: Ibn Hazm\'s position dramatically reduces the scope of binding consensus, expanding the range of legitimately contested issues and theoretically enabling any scholar with evidence to depart from "established" positions. His critics: Al-Amidi and Al-Ghazali argue that the Quranic verse ﴿وَمَن يُشَاقِقِ الرَّسُولَ مِن بَعْدِ مَا تَبَيَّنَ لَهُ الْهُدَىٰ وَيَتَّبِعْ غَيْرَ سَبِيلِ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ﴾ (Quran 4:115) establishes that departing from the path of believers (= scholars of any era) is itself prohibited — making Ijma\' theoretically valid even if practically difficult to establish.',
    source: 'Al-Ihkam fi Usul Al-Ahkam (Vol. 4-6), Ibn Hazm; Al-Ihkam, Al-Amidi; Al-Mustasfa, Al-Ghazali; Al-Nubdha Al-Kafiyah fi Ahkam Usul Al-Fiqh, Ibn Hazm; Ibn Hazm: Hayatuhu wa Asruhu, Sa\'id Al-Afghani',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_12',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Explain the classical doctrine of Al-Fiqh Al-Aqalliyyat (jurisprudence of Muslim minorities) — tracing its development from classical Hanafi provisions for Dar Al-Harb to the contemporary frameworks of Taha Jabir Al-Alwani and Yusuf Al-Qaradawi, and critically evaluating their methodological basis.',
    answer: 'Al-Fiqh Al-Aqalliyyat (minority jurisprudence) addresses the unique legal situation of Muslim communities living as minorities in non-Muslim majority societies — a situation that classical fiqh addressed only partially and indirectly. Classical foundations: The Hanafi school developed the most sophisticated classical treatment through the concepts of Dar Al-Islam and Dar Al-Harb. The Hanafi position that certain rulings (like divorce procedure, financial contracts, and criminal law) operate differently in non-Muslim lands is found in As-Sarakhsi\'s Sharh As-Siyar Al-Kabir and Al-Marghinani\'s Al-Hidayah. However, classical Hanafi doctrine generally assumed that Muslims in non-Muslim lands were temporarily present (travelers, captives, merchants) rather than permanent settled communities. The modern problem: permanent Muslim settlement in non-Muslim democratic states creates situations classical fiqh did not contemplate — citizenship, military service in non-Muslim armies, participation in democratic politics, Islamic mortgage financing for home ownership, employment in institutions with some prohibited elements. Al-Alwani\'s framework (Fiqh Al-Aqalliyyat, 2003): minority communities require a distinct fiqh because their context is genuinely different from both classical Dar Al-Islam and temporary sojourn. He grounds this in Maqasid — the objectives of Islamic law in minority contexts must prioritize preservation of religious identity, productive integration, and dawah effectiveness over detailed compliance with rulings designed for majority Muslim contexts. His most controversial claim: Fiqh Al-Aqalliyyat is not a relaxation of Islamic law but a contextual application of its principles. Al-Qaradawi\'s critique of his own earlier work: in Fi Fiqh Al-Aqalliyyat Al-Muslimah he argues that the framework must be grounded in genuine dalil-based ijtihad, not in mere contextual accommodation. His warning against using Fiqh Al-Aqalliyyat as a cover for abandoning Islamic principles under social pressure is significant. Critical evaluation: the methodological gap in both frameworks is the absence of a clear principle distinguishing legitimate contextual application from unprincipled accommodation. The distinction between darurah (genuine necessity invoking textual provisions) and raghbah (mere preference accommodated without textual basis) is inadequately drawn in much contemporary Fiqh Al-Aqalliyyat literature.',
    source: 'Fiqh Al-Aqalliyyat Al-Muslimah, Al-Alwani; Fi Fiqh Al-Aqalliyyat Al-Muslimah, Al-Qaradawi; Sharh As-Siyar Al-Kabir, As-Sarakhsi; Al-Hidayah, Al-Marghinani; Islamic Law and Muslim Minorities, Uriya Shavit',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_13',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the Hanbali doctrine of \'Aqd Al-Istisna\' (manufacturing contract) — how did Ibn Qudamah\'s Al-Mughni establish its permissibility against the classical qiyas objections, and what are its conditions according to Al-Buhuti in Kashf Al-Qina\'?',
    answer: 'The Istisna\' contract — commissioning the manufacture of a specific good for a predetermined price before the item exists — presents a classical jurisprudential challenge because it appears to combine a sale of a non-existent object (bay\' al-ma\'dum, generally prohibited) with a forward contract (salam) whose conditions it does not meet (salam requires full payment upfront and a specified delivery date). Ibn Qudamah\'s treatment in Al-Mughni (Vol. 4) is the most thorough classical analysis. His argument for permissibility: (1) Ijma\' of scholars on the permissibility of commissioning craftsmen in practice — "The Muslims in all lands in all ages have commissioned craftsmen without objection, and this constitutes Ijma\' \'Amali (practical consensus) stronger than theoretical argument." (2) Istihsan over qiyas — the strict qiyas conclusion (prohibition because the object is non-existent) is overridden by the universal practice and the genuine need for such contracts in an economy where craft production is essential. (3) The prohibition of bay\' al-ma\'dum targets gharar (uncertainty leading to dispute) — Istisna\' minimizes gharar through specification of the object, quality, quantity, and delivery expectations, so the underlying cause of the prohibition is absent. Conditions per Al-Buhuti\'s Kashf Al-Qina\': (a) The object must be precisely specified by description, material, quality, and quantity — ambiguity invalidates; (b) The nature of work must be custom manufacture, not sale of existing goods (which would simply be bay\'); (c) The price may be paid upfront, in installments, or at delivery — unlike salam, full upfront payment is not required; (d) Either party may rescind before production begins; (e) If the manufactured item conforms to specifications, the buyer must accept it. Contemporary application in Islamic banking: Istisna\' is the preferred structure for project financing, construction, and asset manufacture — the bank commissions an asset from a manufacturer, then sells it to the client on installment terms (parallel Istisna\').',
    source: 'Al-Mughni (Vol. 4), Ibn Qudamah; Kashf Al-Qina\' (Vol. 3), Al-Buhuti; Al-Mabsut (Vol. 12), As-Sarakhsi; Al-Mu\'amalat Al-Maliyyah Al-Mu\'asirah, Wahba Az-Zuhayli; Istisna\' fi Al-Fiqh Al-Islami, various',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_14',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Analyze the debate between the Hanafi and Maliki schools on the binding nature of \'Aqd Al-Bay\' (contract of sale) before receipt of consideration — what is the Hanafi concept of Khiyar Al-Majlis and why did Imam Malik reject it despite the explicit hadith evidence?',
    answer: 'The controversy over Khiyar Al-Majlis (option of the session — the right of both parties to rescind a completed sale before physically separating) is one of the most significant intra-school debates in Islamic commercial law, touching the deepest questions of contract theory. The hadith evidence: "Al-Mutabay\'i\'an bil-khiyar ma lam yatafarraqa" — "The two parties to a sale retain the option as long as they have not separated" (Sahih Al-Bukhari 2111, Sahih Muslim 1531). This is mutawatir in transmission and absolutely authentic. The Shafi\'i and Hanbali position: the hadith is clear and binding — after concluding a sale verbally but before physically separating, either party may rescind. This is a legal right created by the Shariah regardless of the parties\' intentions. The Hanafi rejection: the Hanafi school holds that a sale concluded by offer and acceptance (ijab and qabul) is immediately binding — there is no post-conclusion option without agreement. Their response to the hadith: (a) "Tafarruq" (separation) in the hadith means separation of offer and acceptance in the same meeting — not physical departure of the parties, which is a Maliki misunderstanding; (b) The hadith is contradicted by the hadith "Whoever buys food must not sell it until he has taken possession" — implying the sale was binding before possession; (c) The analogy with all other contracts — ijara, nikah, khul\' — which become binding at conclusion without any option period. The Maliki rejection is more nuanced: Imam Malik in Al-Muwatta explicitly knows the hadith but considers Amal Ahl Al-Madinah (the practice of the people of Madinah) to contradict it. Since Madinan practice is his highest evidential standard — reflecting the living Sunnah transmitted through continuous community practice rather than individual verbal narration — the hadith does not override it. This is the controversial Maliki principle that Ash-Shafi\'i famously rejected: "Amal cannot override khabar" — Prophetic verbal traditions override community practice when they conflict.',
    source: 'Al-Muwatta, Imam Malik (Kitab Al-Buyu\'); Ar-Risalah, Ash-Shafi\'i; Al-Umm, Ash-Shafi\'i; Al-Mabsut, As-Sarakhsi; Al-Mughni, Ibn Qudamah; Al-Mudawwanah Al-Kubra, Ibn Al-Qasim',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_15',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the classical jurisprudential analysis of Al-Ghasb (usurpation) and its relationship to the principle of Ad-Darar Yuzal — how does Ibn Qudamah\'s treatment in Al-Mughni address the question of Ghasb Al-Manafi\' (usurpation of benefits) and the compensation owed for unusable usurped property?',
    answer: 'Ghasb (usurpation — taking another\'s property by force without legal right) is one of the most extensively analyzed topics in classical fiqh because it raises the deepest questions about property, benefit, and compensation. The foundational principle: Ad-Darar Yuzal (harm must be eliminated) — the usurper is obligated to restore the exact usurped property if extant, or its equivalent if destroyed, and to compensate for benefits lost during the usurpation period. The contested question — Ghasb Al-Manafi\' (usurpation of benefits): if someone takes another\'s house by force but does not damage the building — merely occupying and using it for a year — must they pay rent for the benefit they consumed even though they return the house intact? The Hanafi position (the most discussed): no compensation is owed for benefits (manafi\') in usurpation because benefits are not "things" (a\'yan) — they are destroyed as they arise and cannot be compensated. The usurper owes only the return of the property itself. If the property is damaged, they owe the difference in value. But the year of occupancy, the benefit consumed, is not compensable. This position is criticized as creating a windfall for wrongdoers. The Shafi\'i and Hanbali position (Ibn Qudamah\'s Al-Mughni, Vol. 5): compensation is owed for all benefits consumed, whether or not the property itself is damaged, because: (a) The Prophet ﷺ said "al-kharaj bid-daman" (benefit follows liability) — implying that one who bears liability for property owns its benefits; conversely, one who wrongfully holds property owes its benefits; (b) The principle of Ad-Darar Yuzal requires full elimination of harm — allowing the usurper to retain the benefit of occupation creates ongoing harm to the owner; (c) The ijara (rental) principle establishes the market value of property use, which the usurper has consumed without right. Ibn Qudamah\'s sophisticated addition: even if the usurped property is not typically rented — a private home the owner never leases — the usurper owes the market rental equivalent, because the owner\'s right to use or rent is the underlying property right violated.',
    source: 'Al-Mughni (Vol. 5), Ibn Qudamah; Al-Mabsut (Vol. 11), As-Sarakhsi; Al-Mudawwanah, Sahnun; Al-Umm, Ash-Shafi\'i; Rawdat At-Talibin, An-Nawawi',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_16',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Explain the Maliki doctrine of Muraa\'at Al-Khilaf (consideration of scholarly disagreement) as developed by Al-Qarafi in Ash-Shuruq and As-Suyuti in Al-Ashbah wa An-Naza\'ir — when is it a scholarly virtue and when does it become impermissible Talfiq?',
    answer: 'Muraa\'at Al-Khilaf (giving consideration to scholarly disagreement — specifically, acting in ways that honor the valid positions of other schools) is one of the most sophisticated concepts in later Islamic jurisprudence. It is distinct from Talfiq (problematic patching of different opinions) and represents a mature approach to intra-school plurality. Al-Qarafi\'s development in Ash-Shuruq: Muraa\'at Al-Khilaf is recommended (mandub) when performing an act that the scholarly disagreement suggests might be invalid in one\'s own madhab. Example: a Shafi\'i who touches his wife before prayer (which breaks wudu in the Shafi\'i school) but has not voided wudu by another means — the Maliki position is that such touching does not break wudu. The Shafi\'i should consider performing new wudu out of caution for the disagreement (muraa\'at al-khilaf), not because they have adopted the Maliki position, but because the existence of strong disagreement creates jurisprudential uncertainty. As-Suyuti\'s Al-Ashbah wa An-Naza\'ir systematizes this under the legal maxim "Al-Khuruj min Al-Khilaf Mustahabb" (exiting scholarly disagreement is recommended) — when one can perform an act in a way that all valid schools would consider valid, this is preferred over performing it in a way that one valid school considers invalid. The limit: Muraa\'at Al-Khilaf is impermissible when it requires violating a definite ruling of one\'s own madhab merely to honor a weak or marginal opinion of another. And when it collapses into Talfiq — selecting the most convenient opinion from each school in a pattern no single school would validate — it is prohibited. The test: would an imam of any one school, presented with the combined ruling, consider the resulting act valid? If no single school validates the combined result, the act is invalid regardless of how many schools each component was drawn from.',
    source: 'Ash-Shuruq wa Al-Ghuruq, Al-Qarafi; Al-Ashbah wa An-Naza\'ir, As-Suyuti; Al-Ashbah wa An-Naza\'ir, Ibn Nujaym; Usul Al-Fiqh Al-Islami, Az-Zuhayli; Mawahib Al-Jalil, Al-Hattab',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_17',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the jurisprudential basis for the prohibition of Riba Al-Fadl (riba of surplus in exchange of same-kind goods) — analyze the hadith of the six ribawi commodities and the scholarly disagreement on the \'illah (effective cause), particularly the Hanafi, Maliki, and Shafi\'i positions.',
    answer: 'Riba Al-Fadl (surplus riba) is the prohibition on exchanging same-species goods in unequal quantities, established by the hadith: "Gold for gold, silver for silver, wheat for wheat, barley for barley, dates for dates, salt for salt — like for like, equal for equal, hand to hand. Whoever gives more or takes more has dealt in riba." (Sahih Muslim 1584) This is mutawatir and unambiguous. The contested question is the \'illah — the effective cause that allows extension of this prohibition by qiyas to other commodities beyond the six named: (1) The Hanafi position: the \'illah is Jins (species) + Qadr (measured by weight or volume). Gold and silver are prohibited because they are of the same species and measured by weight. Wheat, barley, dates, and salt are prohibited because they are of the same species and measured by volume. Extension: any commodity exchanged by weight (copper, iron, cotton) is subject to riba al-fadl within the same species. The logic: the Hanafi \'illah is formal/categorical. (2) The Maliki position: the \'illah is Qut wa Iddikar (nutritional value + storability) for foodstuffs, and Thamaniyyah (monetary function) for gold and silver. Extension: any storable food that serves nutritional purposes is subject to riba al-fadl within the same species. Non-storable fruits, cooked foods, and non-nutritional commodities are excluded. (3) The Shafi\'i and Hanbali position: the \'illah for foodstuffs is simply Ta\'am (edibility/food nature), and for gold and silver is Thamaniyyah. Extension: any edible commodity — even fresh fruit and cooked food — is subject to riba al-fadl. This is the broadest position. The scholarly consequence of these differences: a Hanafi can exchange copper for copper in unequal quantities by weight without riba concern (if not currency), while a Shafi\'i cannot exchange any food for its kind in unequal quantities regardless of monetary function. Contemporary application in Islamic finance: the \'illah controversy determines whether riba rules apply to commodities used as hedging instruments, currency exchange differentials, and modern financial derivatives.',
    source: 'Sahih Muslim 1584; Fath Al-Bari (Kitab Al-Buyu\'), Ibn Hajar; Al-Mughni (Vol. 4), Ibn Qudamah; Al-Mabsut (Vol. 12), As-Sarakhsi; Bidayat Al-Mujtahid, Ibn Rushd; Al-Muqaddamat Al-Mumahhidat, Ibn Rushd',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_18',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Analyze the concept of Dhara\'i\' in Imam Malik\'s jurisprudence through the lens of Al-Mudawwanah Al-Kubra — how does Sahnun\'s compilation reflect Malik\'s approach to blocking means that lead to harm even when the means themselves are permissible, and what distinguishes Maliki application from Hanbali application?',
    answer: 'Imam Malik\'s application of Sadd Al-Dhara\'i\' in Al-Mudawwanah Al-Kubra (as compiled by Sahnun from Ibn Al-Qasim\'s transmission of Malik\'s teaching) reveals a jurisprudential sensibility distinct from the more systematic Hanbali application. Malik\'s approach is contextual and sociological rather than principled and categorical — he applies Sadd Al-Dhara\'i\' differently based on the social context, community norms, and the realistic expectation of what the action will lead to. Examples from Al-Mudawwanah: (1) Marriage with the intention of divorce: Malik held this prohibited (the classic Sadd Al-Dhara\'i\' case) because in Madinan society the practice was recognizable as a stratagem to "legalize" what was effectively temporary marriage — but he did not hold the marriage invalid if it was not discovered to be intended as such. (2) The sale of grapes to a winemaker: Malik prohibits it in a context where the seller knows the buyer will make wine, applying Sadd Al-Dhara\'i\'. But unlike Ibn Taymiyyah\'s Hanbali application (which emphasizes the moral responsibility of the seller regardless of what can be proven), Malik requires actual knowledge of intent — mere probability of misuse does not prohibit the sale. (3) Bay\' Al-\'Inah (buying something back at a lower price to achieve a disguised loan): Malik prohibits more broadly than the Shafi\'i school based on Sadd Al-Dhara\'i\', but requires that the structure actually resemble riba in its functional outcome — not merely that it could theoretically be used for that purpose. The key Maliki-Hanbali distinction: Malik applies Sadd Al-Dhara\'i\' primarily where the action is specifically and recognizably designed to circumvent a prohibition in the context of the actual transaction and parties. Ibn Taymiyyah extends it to structural patterns that reliably lead to harm regardless of individual intent. The Maliki position is therefore more party-specific and context-sensitive; the Hanbali position is more categorical and structural.',
    source: 'Al-Mudawwanah Al-Kubra (Vol. 3-4), Sahnun; Al-Muwatta, Imam Malik; Al-Istidhkar, Ibn \'Abd Al-Barr; Bidayat Al-Mujtahid, Ibn Rushd; Mawahib Al-Jalil, Al-Hattab',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_19',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the classical doctrine of Al-Mafqud (the missing person) and its legal consequences — analyze how the four schools determine the waiting period before presuming death, the treatment of the missing person\'s property, and the marital status of their spouse, with particular attention to Ibn Qudamah\'s position.',
    answer: 'Al-Mafqud (the missing person) presents one of classical fiqh\'s most nuanced problems because it requires the jurist to make binding legal rulings about a person whose status — living or dead — is genuinely unknown. The case divides into several interrelated sub-questions. (1) The waiting period before presuming death: The Maliki school is the most flexible — Imam Malik in Al-Muwatta holds that the judge determines the period based on circumstances (battle, sea voyage, etc.), and a famous Maliki position holds four years for normal disappearance, shorter for dangerous circumstances. The Shafi\'i and Hanbali traditional positions: ninety years from birth (the maximum expected lifespan), after which the person is presumed dead. Ibn Qudamah in Al-Mughni critiques this as practically absurd — it means a person missing from age twenty would not be presumed dead for seventy years, leaving their estate, spouse, and affairs in permanent uncertainty. He prefers the Maliki flexibility of judicial determination. The Hanafi position: four years in cases where the disappearance suggests death (battle, sea), otherwise lifespan. (2) The missing person\'s property: by consensus, their estate is not distributed until death is established — either through direct evidence, witnesses, or judicial ruling of presumed death. The property is preserved and administered. Income from the property (crops, rent) is preserved in trust, not distributed. (3) The spouse\'s status: this is the most consequential and contested. Hanafi: the wife cannot remarry until either the husband returns or his death is established — there is no judicial dissolution for mere disappearance. Maliki: after the judicially determined waiting period, the wife may petition for divorce by faskh (judicial annulment), receive iddah, then remarry. Shafi\'i: follows the Hanafi position (cannot remarry without evidence of death) though later Shafi\'i scholars adopted the Maliki position in practice. The humanitarian argument for the Maliki position: the Quran commands "either retain in goodness or release in goodness" — indefinitely suspending a woman in marital limbo without any relief violates this command.',
    source: 'Al-Mughni (Vol. 6), Ibn Qudamah; Al-Muwatta (Kitab At-Talaq), Imam Malik; Al-Mabsut, As-Sarakhsi; Rawdat At-Talibin, An-Nawawi; Al-Mudawwanah, Sahnun',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_20',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Explain the doctrine of Fiqh An-Nawazil (jurisprudence of novel cases) and the methodology for deriving rulings for unprecedented situations — what are the five stages of the istinbat process as described by Ibn \'Abd As-Salam in Qawa\'id Al-Ahkam, and how does contemporary Fiqh An-Nawazil differ from classical applications?',
    answer: 'Fiqh An-Nawazil (jurisprudence of newly arising cases — "nawazil" means cases that "fall upon" a community without established precedent) is the domain of Islamic law that demonstrates the tradition\'s capacity for development and adaptation. Ibn \'Abd As-Salam\'s Qawa\'id Al-Ahkam fi Masalih Al-Anam is the foundational work for the methodology of deriving rulings for novel cases through maslahah-based reasoning. His five-stage istinbat process: (1) Tashih Al-Mas\'alah (verification of the case) — precise description of the actual factual situation before any legal analysis begins. Many errors in Islamic legal reasoning begin with imprecise description of the case. What exactly is the novel situation? What are its material components? What differentiates it from existing precedents? (2) Fahs Al-Adillah Al-Juz\'iyyah (examination of particular evidences) — searching all four primary sources and all recognized secondary sources for any indication relevant to this specific case. Ibn \'Abd As-Salam emphasizes that this requires genuine scholarship: not merely searching for the opinion one wants, but comprehensively examining what each source actually indicates. (3) Al-Qiyas wa Al-Ilhaq (analogy and alignment) — identifying the closest established case and analyzing whether the \'illah (effective cause) is shared. This stage requires the jurist to articulate explicitly why the comparison holds or does not hold. (4) Al-I\'tibar bil-Maqasid (consideration of objectives) — asking whether the ruling derived through analogy serves or undermines the objectives of Islamic law. If a technically valid analogy produces a result that clearly violates a maqsad, the analogy is defective and must be re-examined. (5) Al-Fatwa wa At-Tadbir (the ruling and its implementation) — the actual ruling must account for how it will function in practice. A ruling technically correct but practically impossible to implement, or one that will produce outcomes worse than what it seeks to prevent, requires modification at the implementation level. Contemporary Fiqh An-Nawazil — particularly in bioethics, fintech, and environmental jurisprudence — differs from classical applications primarily in the complexity of the factual situation at stage (1): modern bioethical questions require the jurist to understand molecular biology, modern financial questions require understanding of derivatives pricing, and environmental questions require ecological science. The classical jurist could personally master the relevant sciences; the contemporary jurist must rely on expert testimony, creating a new methodological challenge of evaluating scientific consensus within the fiqhi framework.',
    source: 'Qawa\'id Al-Ahkam fi Masalih Al-Anam, Ibn \'Abd As-Salam; Al-Furuq, Al-Qarafi; Fiqh An-Nawazil, Bakr Abu Zayd; Al-Fiqh Al-Islami wa Adillatuhu, Az-Zuhayli; Nawazil Az-Zakah, various',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_21',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Analyze the scholarly debate on the permissibility of organ transplantation in Islamic law — what are the primary objections based on Hurmah Al-Mayyit (sanctity of the deceased), and how do scholars like Ibn Bayyah and Al-Qaradawi argue for its permissibility through the hierarchy of Maqasid?',
    answer: 'The Islamic legal question of organ transplantation involves a genuine collision between two established principles: Hurmah Al-Mayyit (the sanctity and inviolability of the deceased human body) and Hifz An-Nafs (preservation of life — the second maqsad). The primary objection: The Prophet ﷺ said "Breaking the bone of a dead person is like breaking it when they are alive" (Sunan Abu Dawud 3207, authenticated) — establishing that mutilation of the deceased is as prohibited as mutilation of the living. Organ harvesting is precisely this. Secondary objection: the human body is an amanah (trust) from Allah, not property that can be donated or disposed of. The person has no ownership over their organs to donate them. The arguments for permissibility: (1) The Daruri Maqsad of Hifz An-Nafs (preservation of life) is one of the five essential objectives. When a person will die without an organ transplant and a compatible organ is available from a consenting deceased donor, the preservation of life creates a necessity (darurah) that overrides the normal prohibition. Ibn \'Abd As-Salam\'s principle: "Necessities permit what is otherwise prohibited, to the extent of the necessity." (2) The prohibition of "breaking bones" is directed at disrespect and mutilation without benefit. Organ transplantation is not motivated by disrespect but by the preservation of another life — the maqsad (purpose) is entirely different. (3) Islamic law permits autopsy for judicial purposes (establishing cause of death in murder cases) by majority scholarly opinion — this involves more "mutilation" than organ harvesting and is permitted for a lesser interest (justice) than the direct preservation of life. Ibn Bayyah\'s contribution: his concept of Al-Masalih Al-Mu\'tabarah (recognized interests) in the context of organ donation — the deceased\'s prior consent transforms the act from desecration to gift (hibah) — the \'illah (cause) of the prohibition (disrespect) is eliminated by the voluntary donation. OIC Fiqh Academy Resolution 26 (1988) permits organ transplantation under conditions: prior donor consent, no commercial transaction, necessity, and no resulting harm to the donor.',
    source: 'OIC Fiqh Academy Resolutions 26 and 57; Fi Fiqh Al-Aqalliyyat, Al-Qaradawi; Maqasid Ash-Shariah, Ibn Bayyah; Fiqh An-Nawazil fi Al-Tibb, various; Qawa\'id Al-Ahkam, Ibn \'Abd As-Salam',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_22',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the principle of Al-\'Aql Ka-\'Illah in Hanafi jurisprudence — how does the concept of Ahlliyyah (legal capacity) differ between the Hanafi treatment in Usul As-Sarakhsi and the Shafi\'i treatment in Al-Ghazali\'s Al-Mustasfa, particularly regarding the legal acts of the insane (majnun) and the child (sabiyy)?',
    answer: 'The Hanafi theory of Ahlliyyah (legal capacity) as developed in As-Sarakhsi\'s Usul represents the most sophisticated classical account of legal personhood and capacity. The Hanafi distinction between Ahliyyat Al-Wujub (passive capacity — the capacity to have rights and obligations attributed to one) and Ahliyyat Al-Ada\' (active capacity — the capacity to perform legally effective acts) is maintained with subtle gradations not found in the Shafi\'i account. The Hanafi position on \'aql (reason) as the basis of active capacity leads to several important consequences for the insane (majnun) and child (sabiyy mumayyiz): (1) Madnun (insane person): has Ahliyyat Al-Wujub but lacks Ahliyyat Al-Ada\'. His commercial transactions are void (batil) in the Hanafi school — even if apparently beneficial to him — because he lacks the mental capacity that makes consent meaningful. However — and this is distinctively Hanafi — a committee (wali) can transact on his behalf, and these transactions bind him. The Shafi\'i position: the insane person\'s transactions are voidable (fasid) not void — the court may ratify beneficial transactions. (2) Sabiyy Mumayyiz (discerning child): the Hanafi school draws the most detailed gradations. Purely beneficial transactions (accepting gifts) are valid without guardian approval. Purely harmful transactions (gifts away) are void. Mixed transactions (sales, purchases) require guardian ratification. The Hanafi justification: the mumayyiz child has partial \'aql — sufficient to understand the concept of benefit and harm, insufficient to act entirely independently. The Shafi\'i position is simpler: all transactions of the child require guardian oversight regardless of categorization. As-Sarakhsi\'s methodological point: the graduated Hanafi approach better tracks the actual cognitive development of persons — "Ahlliyyah is not binary but exists in degrees proportional to the development of \'aql, and the law should track this gradation."',
    source: 'Usul As-Sarakhsi (Vol. 2), As-Sarakhsi; Al-Mustasfa (Vol. 1), Al-Ghazali; Al-Mabsut (Vol. 2), As-Sarakhsi; Al-Badai\' As-Sanai\', Al-Kasani; Rawdat At-Talibin, An-Nawawi',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_23',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Explain the classical doctrine of Al-Hajr (judicial restriction of legal capacity) — what are its causes and categories, and how does the Maliki treatment in Al-Mudawwanah differ from the Hanbali treatment in Al-Mughni regarding restriction for Safah (financial imprudence)?',
    answer: 'Al-Hajr (judicial restriction of legal capacity) is the power of the court to restrict a legally capable adult\'s right to transact independently — not because they lack mental capacity, but because they will misuse it. The classical causes of Hajr: (1) Safah (financial imprudence/prodigality): the person squanders their wealth in ways that harm themselves and their dependents. (2) Marad Al-Mawt (death illness): a person near death has their capacity to dispose of more than one-third of their estate restricted to protect the rights of heirs. (3) Muflis (insolvency): a debtor\'s assets are restricted by court order to satisfy creditors. (4) Raqqiq (slave): traditional fiqh restricted the slave\'s transactional capacity (largely historically irrelevant). The Maliki-Hanbali difference on Safah (prodigality): The Maliki position in Al-Mudawwanah: Hajr for Safah may be applied even to adults who have always been prodigal — there is no requirement that they previously had full capacity and then lost it through prodigality. The court may impose Hajr on any adult whose financial decisions consistently harm themselves and their dependents, regardless of their history. This is justified by the Maqsad of Hifz Al-Mal (preservation of wealth). The Hanbali position in Al-Mughni: Ibn Qudamah argues that Hajr for Safah requires the jurist to be extremely cautious — restricting an adult\'s legal capacity is a serious infringement on their freedom. He requires not merely that the person makes poor financial decisions, but that the poor decisions have a pattern suggesting genuine cognitive inability to manage finances rather than merely choosing to spend in ways others disapprove of. His concern: "The ruler should not restrict the capacity of people based on his own view of what constitutes good financial management — that would be tyranny." The Shafi\'i middle position: Hajr may be imposed but requires demonstration that the person consistently makes ruinous financial decisions despite warning and counseling.',
    source: 'Al-Mudawwanah Al-Kubra (Vol. 4), Sahnun; Al-Mughni (Vol. 4), Ibn Qudamah; Al-Mabsut (Vol. 24), As-Sarakhsi; Al-Badai\' As-Sanai\', Al-Kasani; Mawahib Al-Jalil, Al-Hattab',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_24',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the classical analysis of Aqd Al-Muzara\'ah (sharecropping contract) — how does Ibn Qudamah establish its permissibility against the Shafi\'i position of prohibition, and what is the decisive hadith evidence that As-Sahih Al-Bukhary reports in Kitab Al-Muzara\'ah?',
    answer: 'The Muzara\'ah contract — a partnership where one party provides land and the other provides labor, with the harvest split by agreed percentage — is one of the most debated agricultural contracts in classical fiqh, with the Shafi\'i school historically prohibiting it and the Hanafi, Maliki, and Hanbali schools permitting it. The Shafi\'i prohibition rests on the hadith: "Whoever has land should either cultivate it himself, or let his brother cultivate it, or leave it fallow" (Sahih Al-Bukhari 2340) — interpreted as prohibiting sharecropping arrangements. Additionally, the general principle prohibiting contracts with uncertain returns: the harvest might fail, leaving one party with nothing and making the "price" (the share of harvest) entirely uncertain at contract time. Ibn Qudamah\'s Al-Mughni (Vol. 5) provides the decisive Hanbali response: (1) The Prophet ﷺ contracted with the Jews of Khaybar to cultivate their date palms and farms in exchange for half the produce (Sahih Al-Bukhari 2329, 2499) — this is explicit Prophetic practice of Muzara\'ah and Musaqah (orchard sharecropping) and constitutes direct Sunnah evidence. (2) The Prophet ﷺ said "Let him give it to his brother without rent" in the context of excessive rent, not sharecropping — the command is directed at exploitative land rental, not at fair partnership arrangements. (3) The uncertainty (gharar) in Muzara\'ah is the same as the uncertainty in Musaqah (orchard partnership) and Mudharabah (capital-labor partnership) — both are permitted by consensus. If gharar alone prohibited such contracts, all partnerships would be prohibited. The Shafi\'i later majority (including Al-Nawawi himself) acknowledged that the Khaybar evidence is compelling and that the Imam Ash-Shafi\'i\'s original prohibition may have been based on incomplete examination of the hadith evidence — a remarkable concession. Al-Nawawi in Al-Majmu\' reviews the evidence and expresses personal agreement with Ibn Qudamah\'s position while maintaining the official Shafi\'i ruling.',
    source: 'Al-Mughni (Vol. 5), Ibn Qudamah; Sahih Al-Bukhari 2329 (Kitab Al-Muzara\'ah); Al-Majmu\', An-Nawawi; Fath Al-Bari (Vol. 5), Ibn Hajar; Al-Mabsut, As-Sarakhsi',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_25',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Analyze the doctrine of Al-Waqf (endowment/charitable trust) in classical Islamic law — what are its conditions for validity, the Hanafi position on the irrevocability of Waqf, and Ibn Taymiyyah\'s controversial view on the permissibility of conditional and revocable Waqf?',
    answer: 'Al-Waqf (the Islamic charitable endowment — permanent dedication of property to a charitable or religious purpose) is one of Islamic civilization\'s most distinctive legal institutions, historically underpinning mosques, madrasas, hospitals, libraries, and infrastructure across the Muslim world. Classical conditions for validity: (1) The Waqif (endower) must be legally competent (adult, sane, free). (2) The property (mawquf) must be precisely defined and owned by the Waqif. (3) The purpose (mawquf \'alayh) must be religiously legitimate and continuing — the endowment must serve a purpose that persists indefinitely. (4) Irrevocability: the dominant position across all four schools holds that once validly established, a Waqf cannot be revoked by the endower, dissolved for the benefit of heirs, or transferred. This irrevocability is what distinguishes Waqf from ordinary charitable donation and makes it the basis for perpetual institutions. The Hanafi position on irrevocability: uniquely, the early Hanafi school (including Abu Hanifah himself in the famous transmission from Muhammad ibn Al-Hasan) held that Waqf is not binding (lazim) — the endower may revoke it during their lifetime. This position was rejected by Abu Yusuf and Muhammad (Abu Hanifah\'s two leading students) who held irrevocability — and the later Hanafi school follows Abu Yusuf and Muhammad on this. The practical consequence: Ottoman Waqf law, built on Hanafi principles, adopted the irrevocability position despite Abu Hanifah\'s theoretical dissent. Ibn Taymiyyah\'s controversial position: in Majmoo\' Al-Fatawa, he permits conditional and time-limited Waqf — a Waqf that lasts for a specified period (e.g., "This house is Waqf for the madrasa for 50 years") or is conditional ("This Waqf is for my children; if they have no descendants the property reverts to me"). His reasoning: the textual evidence for irrevocability is weaker than claimed, and conditional agreements are generally valid in Islamic law. This position enables more flexible use of Waqf instruments in modern Islamic finance and social institutions.',
    source: 'Majmoo\' Al-Fatawa (Vol. 31), Ibn Taymiyyah; Al-Mabsut (Vol. 12), As-Sarakhsi; Al-Mughni (Vol. 5), Ibn Qudamah; Mawahib Al-Jalil, Al-Hattab; Ahkam Al-Awqaf, Abu Bakr Al-Khassaf',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_26',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the jurisprudential basis for the prohibition of Mutah (temporary marriage) — how does Ibn Hazm\'s position in Al-Muhalla defend its permissibility against the scholarly consensus, and what is the most compelling response to his hadith-based argument?',
    answer: 'Mut\'ah (temporary marriage — a marriage contracted for a specified period) was practiced in the early Islamic period and is documented in multiple authentic hadiths. The scholarly consensus (ijma\') of Sunni Islam holds it was definitively prohibited by the Prophet ﷺ before his death, making it haram in Islamic law. Ibn Hazm\'s position in Al-Muhalla is the most sophisticated Sunni dissent from this consensus — notably, he argues for prohibition in the end but surveys the evidence so thoroughly that his analysis reveals the genuine complexity. The hadith evidence for final prohibition: (1) Ali ibn Abi Talib reported: "The Prophet ﷺ prohibited Mut\'ah marriages and the flesh of domestic donkeys on the day of Khaybar" (Sahih Al-Bukhari 4216, Sahih Muslim 1407). (2) Sabra Al-Juhanni reported that the Prophet ﷺ commanded abandonment of Mut\'ah in the Farewell Pilgrimage: "I had permitted you to engage in Mut\'ah with women, but Allah has now prohibited it until the Day of Resurrection." (Sahih Muslim 1406) (3) Umar ibn Al-Khattab\'s prohibition — cited by the Shia as evidence that it was Umar who prohibited it, not the Prophet ﷺ — is addressed by Sunni scholars as Umar publicly reaffirming the Prophet\'s prohibition, not innovating one. Ibn Hazm\'s methodological challenge: he notes that some Companions (including Abdullah ibn \'Abbas) apparently permitted Mut\'ah after the Prophet\'s death as an extreme necessity provision, suggesting the final prohibition was not universally transmitted. The response of Ibn Hajar in Fath Al-Bari: Ibn \'Abbas\'s position was a personal ijtihad based on incomplete information — he later retracted it when the hadith of Sabra was brought to his attention, and in any case individual Companion opinion does not override authentic Prophetic prohibition. The Shia argument (not Ibn Hazm\'s): that Mut\'ah was prohibited by Umar not by the Prophet ﷺ is refuted by Ali ibn Abi Talib\'s own hadith attributing the prohibition to the Prophet ﷺ — Ali, the Shia Imam par excellence, is himself the primary source for the Prophetic prohibition.',
    source: 'Al-Muhalla (Vol. 9), Ibn Hazm; Sahih Muslim 1406-1407; Fath Al-Bari (Vol. 9), Ibn Hajar; Al-Mughni (Vol. 7), Ibn Qudamah; Nayl Al-Awtar, Ash-Shawkani',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_27',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Explain the doctrine of Kaffarah (expiation) across the five categories established in the Quran — how does the hierarchy of options within each Kaffarah reflect the Maqasid of calibrating penalty to capability, and what is the Hanafi-Shafi\'i disagreement on whether Kaffarah is sequentially ordered or simultaneously optional?',
    answer: 'Kaffarah (expiation — making amends for a specified transgression through a prescribed act) appears in the Quran across five categories: (1) Kaffarah Al-Yamin (oath expiation — Quran 5:89): feeding ten poor persons, or clothing them, or freeing a slave — if unable, three days fasting. (2) Kaffarah Az-Zihar (declaration of wives like mothers — Quran 58:3-4): freeing a slave; if unable, fasting two consecutive months; if unable, feeding sixty poor persons. (3) Kaffarah Al-Ifi\' (oath of sexual abstinence from wife — Quran 2:226): expiation required before resumption. (4) Kaffarah Al-Qatl Al-Khata\' (accidental killing — Quran 4:92): freeing a slave; if unable, fasting two consecutive months. (5) Kaffarah Sayd Al-Haram (hunting in the Haram — Quran 5:95): equivalent sacrifice, or feeding the poor, or fasting. The Hanafi-Shafi\'i disagreement on Kaffarah Al-Yamin: The Shafi\'i position (and majority): the three options (feeding, clothing, freeing) are simultaneously available — the person may choose any of the three. Only when all three are impossible is fasting required. This is Ta\'yir (selection from simultaneously available options). The Hanafi position: the three options are ordered (tarteeb) — the person must attempt feeding first. Only if genuinely unable (due to poverty, not mere preference) may they proceed to clothing. Only if unable to clothe may they free a slave. Fasting is only for those unable to do any of the three. This Hanafi position — which Ibn Qudamah in Al-Mughni acknowledges produces a more demanding standard — is based on their reading of the Arabic \'aw (or) in the verse as indicating sequential preference, not simultaneous choice. The Maqasid dimension: the hierarchy of Kaffarah options reflects the principle that Islamic law calibrates obligations to capability — the same moral weight of expiation is achieved through different acts depending on the person\'s circumstances.',
    source: 'Al-Mabsut (Vol. 8), As-Sarakhsi; Al-Mughni (Vol. 9), Ibn Qudamah; Al-Majmu\' (Vol. 15), An-Nawawi; Al-Muqaddamat, Ibn Rushd; Zad Al-Mustaqni\', Al-Hajjawi',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_28',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the classical doctrine of \'Aqilah (collective blood money) — analyze its foundations, the Hanafi-Maliki debate on who constitutes the \'Aqilah, and Ibn Taymiyyah\'s position on whether this doctrine represents a principle of collective liability that can be extended to other areas of law.',
    answer: '\'Aqilah (the collective — specifically, the group liable to pay blood money in cases of accidental killing) is one of Islamic law\'s most distinctive doctrines, representing what modern legal theory would call collective liability without individual fault. The Prophetic foundation: the Prophet ﷺ established that in cases of accidental killing (qatl khata\'), the blood money (diyah) is paid by the \'Aqilah of the killer — not by the killer personally — over three years. (Al-Muwatta, Kitab Al-\'Uqul; Sunan Abu Dawud 4576.) The composition of the \'Aqilah is the primary point of disagreement: (1) The Maliki position: the \'Aqilah consists of the killer\'s Asabat (patrilineal agnates) — brothers, paternal uncles, their sons, etc. The closer the relationship, the larger the share. The state (bayt al-mal) assumes responsibility when no \'Aqilah exists or their resources are insufficient. (2) The Hanafi position: historically the \'Aqilah was the killer\'s military unit (diwan — the regiment they were enrolled in during early Islamic administration). When military registration ceased to be universal, the \'Aqilah becomes the professional guild or occupational group — reflecting the administrative reality that people\'s primary social solidarity in urban settings is their professional community. (3) The Hanbali position: the \'Aqilah is the killer\'s tribe — or in the absence of tribal structure, their patrilineal family. Ibn Taymiyyah\'s extension of the \'Aqilah principle: in several places in Majmoo\' Al-Fatawa he argues that the \'Aqilah principle reflects a deep Islamic social philosophy — that harm arising from within a group creates collective responsibility for that group to make amends. He sees this as legitimating collective insurance arrangements, occupational guild liability systems, and even certain forms of communal taxation for public welfare. This interpretation has influenced contemporary Islamic insurance (takaful) theory: the takaful pool functions like an expanded \'Aqilah — the community collectively absorbs risks that would destroy any individual member.',
    source: 'Majmoo\' Al-Fatawa (Vol. 34), Ibn Taymiyyah; Al-Muwatta (Kitab Al-\'Uqul), Imam Malik; Al-Mabsut (Vol. 26), As-Sarakhsi; Al-Mughni (Vol. 8), Ibn Qudamah; Takaful: Concept and Practice, various',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_29',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Analyze the concept of Al-Istihalah (transformation/transmutation) in Islamic purity law — how does the Hanafi doctrine that chemical transformation (istihalah) purifies an originally impure substance (e.g., wine becoming vinegar) differ from the Maliki and Shafi\'i positions, and what is the contemporary application to pharmaceutical gelatin and enzymatic products?',
    answer: 'Al-Istihalah (complete chemical/physical transformation) addresses the fundamental question of whether transforming an impure or prohibited substance into a chemically different substance changes its legal status. The foundational case: khamr (wine) that naturally converts to vinegar (khall). All four schools agree that wine that becomes vinegar through natural fermentation is pure and permissible — the evidence is the Prophet ﷺ\'s statement "What excellent vinegar is vinegar" (Sahih Muslim 3817) and the Companions\' use of vinegar without concern for its origins. The contested question: does this apply to intentionally produced transformation, and how far does the principle extend? The Hanafi position (the most expansive): Istihalah produces tahir (purification) whenever the transformation is complete — when the original substance\'s chemical properties, taste, smell, color, and physical characteristics have entirely changed. This is derived from the legal maxim "If the substance transforms, the ruling transforms" (Idha tabaddala al-\'ayn tabaddala al-hukm). Applications: (a) Fat rendered from a pig, when chemically converted through saponification into soap, becomes pure (this position is held by some Hanafi scholars though contested); (b) Alcohol used in perfumes, if present in quantities too small to produce intoxication and chemically different from beverage alcohol, is permissible; (c) Bone char from pork used to filter sugar becomes pure after processing. The Maliki and Shafi\'i position (more restrictive): Istihalah purifies only what the Shariah has specifically indicated is purified — wine becoming vinegar is explicitly supported by the Sunnah. General chemical transformation does not automatically produce tahir status for any originally prohibited substance. Contemporary pharmaceutical gelatin: derived from pork collagen, processed through acid or alkaline hydrolysis. The Hanafi argument for permissibility: complete istihalah — gelatin shares no chemical properties with the original collagen, and shares nothing with pork tissue. The Maliki-Shafi\'i argument for prohibition: the chemical transformation is not complete in the meaningful sense — the protein backbone, amino acid sequences, and biological function are preserved. The gelatin is pork protein in a different physical form, not a new substance.',
    source: 'Al-Mabsut (Vol. 24), As-Sarakhsi; Al-Majmu\' (Vol. 1), An-Nawawi; Majallat Al-Majma\' Al-Fiqhi Al-Islami (various issues); Istihalah fi Al-Fiqh Al-Islami, various scholars; Modern Halal Standards, JAKIM, MUI',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_30',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the classical doctrine of Tawbah (repentance) in Islamic jurisprudence — how does Al-Ghazali\'s treatment in Ihya\' \'Ulum Ad-Din\'s Kitab At-Tawbah relate to Ibn Al-Qayyim\'s analysis in Madarij As-Salikin, and what is the fiqhi question of whether sincere Tawbah eliminates the hadd punishment or only the sin?',
    answer: 'Tawbah (repentance) occupies a unique position in Islamic jurisprudence because it sits at the intersection of individual ethics, legal procedure, and theology. Al-Ghazali\'s Kitab At-Tawbah in Ihya\' \'Ulum Ad-Din is the most comprehensive classical treatment of repentance as a spiritual station (maqam). He defines it through three inseparable elements: \'ilm (knowledge of the gravity of the sin), halah (the emotional state of regret), and \'amal (the act of cessation and resolution). His most significant contribution: repentance is not merely the utterance of "astaghfirullah" but a genuine change of state that manifests in behavior. He distinguishes between tawbah from specific sins (repentance for a particular act) and tawbah kulliyyah (comprehensive repentance encompassing one\'s entire relationship with Allah), arguing that the latter is a continuous spiritual condition, not a one-time event. Ibn Al-Qayyim\'s Madarij As-Salikin (his monumental commentary on Ibn Al-Khafif\'s Manazil As-Sa\'irin) extends this into a hierarchical spiritual psychology of repentance. He identifies seven ascending levels of repentance: from cessation of the sin (al-iqla\'), through sincere regret (an-nadam), commitment to non-recurrence (al-\'azm), and restitution of rights (radd al-mazalim), to the highest level of complete return to Allah (inabah and awbah). The fiqhi-legal question: does sincere Tawbah before apprehension eliminate the hadd punishment? The majority position: Tawbah eliminates the sin (before Allah) and remits the punishment in the Akhirah, but does not eliminate the hadd punishment in this world if the person has been caught and brought before a court. The exception: the thief who returns the stolen property before apprehension — some scholars hold this eliminates the hadd. Ibn Taymiyyah\'s nuanced position: for crimes against Allah alone (like drinking alcohol, adultery without a victim seeking restitution), the imam has discretion to pardon the repentant offender, particularly if the crime was self-reported and the person shows genuine reform. This position is based on the case of Ma\'iz Al-Aslami, where the Prophet ﷺ initially attempted to discourage his confession.',
    source: 'Ihya\' \'Ulum Ad-Din (Kitab At-Tawbah), Al-Ghazali; Madarij As-Salikin, Ibn Al-Qayyim; Majmoo\' Al-Fatawa (Vol. 15), Ibn Taymiyyah; At-Tawbah wa Ahkamuha, various scholars',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_31',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Explain Imam Ash-Shafi\'i\'s doctrine of Ijtihad and the limits he places on it in Ar-Risalah — how does his insistence that all ijtihad must be anchored in textual evidence (Qiyas on Nass) distinguish him from both the Hanafi ra\'y tradition and from modern proponents of unrestricted ijtihad?',
    answer: 'Imam Ash-Shafi\'i\'s Ar-Risalah is not merely the first systematic Usul Al-Fiqh text — it is a sustained argument about what Islamic legal reasoning is and must be, written against the backdrop of two tendencies he considered dangerous: the excessive use of ra\'y (personal opinion) in the Hanafi-Kufan tradition, and the excessive restriction of the Madinans who sometimes rejected authentic hadiths in favor of local practice. Ash-Shafi\'i\'s core thesis: all valid legal reasoning (ijtihad) must be grounded in the four sources (Quran, Sunnah, Ijma\', Qiyas on the previous three) — and the most important of these is the Sunnah, which he elevated to co-equality with the Quran against those who treated it as secondary. His restrictions on ijtihad: (1) Qiyas must be grounded in an established nass (textual ruling) as the asl — there is no ijtihad floating free from a textual anchor. Every legal analogy requires identifying: (a) the original case with a Quranic or Sunnah ruling; (b) the new case; (c) the shared \'illah. Without all three, the reasoning is ra\'y, not qiyas. (2) The \'illah must be manifest (zahir) and consistent (muttarid) — it cannot be a private intellectual intuition but must be identifiable by any qualified scholar examining the same texts. (3) Istihsan is prohibited — "whoever uses istihsan has legislated" — because it allows the jurist\'s personal judgment to override the textual structure without transparent accountability. His disagreement with the Hanafi ra\'y tradition: the Hanafis, particularly the Kufan school, sometimes prioritized principles derived from the cumulative logic of the fiqh tradition over individual hadiths. Ash-Shafi\'i insists this gets the methodology backwards — the fiqh tradition must be accountable to authentic hadiths, not the other way around. The modern relevance of Ash-Shafi\'i\'s restriction: contemporary calls for "opening the door of ijtihad" often implicitly reject his textual-anchor requirement, proposing to derive Islamic legal rulings from rational analysis of contemporary welfare without specific textual grounding. Ash-Shafi\'i\'s framework would classify this as ra\'y that has no claim to the authority of Islamic law.',
    source: 'Ar-Risalah, Ash-Shafi\'i (ed. Ahmad Shakir); Al-Umm (Vol. 7, Jimma\' Al-\'Ilm), Ash-Shafi\'i; The Epistle on Legal Theory (translation by Joseph Lowry); Imam Ash-Shafi\'i, Muhammad Abu Zahrah',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_32',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the doctrine of Al-Ghurar (uncertainty) in Islamic contract law — analyze its three levels (kathir/yasir/mutawassit) as identified by Ibn Juzayy in Al-Qawanin Al-Fiqhiyyah, and explain how the permissibility of salam, ijara, and mudarabah despite containing ghurar is reconciled with the prohibition of bay\' al-gharar.',
    answer: 'Ghurar (uncertainty or hazard that may lead to dispute and harm) is the second major category of contractual prohibition in Islamic law after riba — the Prophet ﷺ prohibited "bay\' al-gharar" (sale with gharar) in an authentic hadith (Sahih Muslim 1513). The doctrine\'s sophistication lies in the fact that virtually every contract contains some element of uncertainty — the precise challenge is determining which uncertainty is legally material and which is negligible. Ibn Juzayy Al-Maliki in Al-Qawanin Al-Fiqhiyyah (a concise but remarkably precise Maliki fiqh manual) identifies three levels: (1) Ghurar Kathir (major uncertainty) — uncertainty that affects the core of the contract and would predictably lead to dispute. Examples: selling fish in a pond without count, selling the wool on an animal without weighing it, selling fruit before it appears on the tree. All prohibited. (2) Ghurar Yasir (minor uncertainty) — uncertainty so incidental that parties reasonably accept it without concern and it rarely leads to dispute. Examples: the slight uncertainty about the exact weight of packaged goods, the uncertainty about what direction a garment will face when assembled. All permitted. (3) Ghurar Mutawassit (intermediate uncertainty) — uncertainty that is significant but falls short of making the contract\'s core uncertain. This is where the jurisprudential analysis becomes most sophisticated and where the schools differ. The reconciliation with permissible contracts: (a) Salam (forward sale) — the commodity doesn\'t exist yet (uncertainty about existence), but the contract specifies all material characteristics with precision, and commercial necessity (Hajah) requires it. The ghurar is yasir relative to the specified terms. (b) Ijara (lease) — the benefit hasn\'t yet been delivered (uncertainty about future performance), but the benefit type, duration, and amount are specified. Ghurar yasir. (c) Mudarabah (profit-sharing) — the profit is entirely uncertain. This appears to be ghurar kathir, yet it is permitted by ijma\'. The resolution: the prohibition of ghurar applies to bay\' (sale) structures where one party receives a defined consideration while the other receives an uncertain outcome. Mudarabah is a partnership where both parties share the uncertainty proportionally — there is no asymmetric risk transfer creating unjust enrichment at the other\'s expense.',
    source: 'Al-Qawanin Al-Fiqhiyyah, Ibn Juzayy; Al-Muwafaqat, Ash-Shatibi; Gharar and Its Effect on Contracts, Dr. Siddiq Ad-Dareer; Al-Muhadhdhab, Ash-Shirazi; Bidayat Al-Mujtahid, Ibn Rushd',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_33',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the classical theory of Al-Qisas (retaliation) — analyze the conditions for Qisas in cases of intentional killing as discussed by An-Nawawi in Rawdat At-Talibin, and explain the doctrine of \'Afw (pardon by the heirs) and its relationship to the Quranic principle ﴿فَمَنْ عُفِيَ لَهُ مِنْ أَخِيهِ شَيْءٌ فَاتِّبَاعٌ بِالْمَعْرُوفِ﴾.',
    answer: 'Qisas (retaliation in kind for intentional killing or injury) is established by the Quran ﴿وَلَكُمْ فِي الْقِصَاصِ حَيَاةٌ يَا أُولِي الْأَلْبَابِ﴾ (Quran 2:179) — "And in Qisas there is life for you, O people of understanding." The classical conditions for Qisas in intentional killing as analyzed in An-Nawawi\'s Rawdat At-Talibin: (1) The killer must be legally responsible (mukallaf — adult, sane, not under compulsion). (2) The killed person must be protected (ma\'sum ad-dam) — a Muslim or protected non-Muslim. No Qisas if the killer kills an unprotected enemy combatant in battle. (3) The killed person must not be a descendant (walad) of the killer — no Qisas for a parent killing their child in all four schools, though the Shafi\'i school requires Qisas if a stranger kills the child with the parent\'s complicity. (4) The killer must not be of a higher status that would be violated by Qisas — the classical (and now largely rejected) position that a Muslim is not killed for killing a dhimmi. (5) Intentionality must be established — accidental killing (qatl khata\') and semi-intentional killing (qatl shibh \'amd) require diyah (blood money) not Qisas. An-Nawawi\'s Rawdat At-Talibin provides the most detailed analysis of the \'Afw (pardon) doctrine. The Quranic verse (2:178): ﴿فَمَنْ عُفِيَ لَهُ مِنْ أَخِيهِ شَيْءٌ فَاتِّبَاعٌ بِالْمَعْرُوفِ وَأَدَاءٌ إِلَيْهِ بِإِحْسَانٍ﴾ — "Whoever is forgiven by his brother (of the killing), let there be adherence to proper conduct and payment to him in kindness." This establishes \'Afw as a legitimate option that creates an obligation of diyah in lieu of Qisas. The classical analysis: the heirs of the victim hold the right to Qisas — not the state. They may: (a) Demand Qisas (execution of the killer); (b) Accept diyah (blood money) in lieu; (c) Pardon entirely (\'afw mutlaq) without compensation — the most morally praised option per the hadith "Allah increases the honor of one who pardons." The state cannot override the heirs\' choice — Qisas is a private right (haqq khass) not a public right. This distinction from modern criminal law — where the state prosecutes regardless of the victim\'s family\'s wishes — is one of the most fundamental structural differences between Islamic criminal law and modern Western systems.',
    source: 'Rawdat At-Talibin (Vol. 9), An-Nawawi; Al-Mughni (Vol. 8), Ibn Qudamah; Al-Mabsut (Vol. 26), As-Sarakhsi; Quran 2:178-179; Fath Al-Qadir, Ibn Humam',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_34',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Explain the Hanbali doctrine of Khul\' (wife-initiated divorce by compensation) — what is Ibn Qudamah\'s analysis of whether the husband\'s consent is required, and how does Ibn Taymiyyah\'s position that Khul\' can be effected through a judge without the husband\'s consent differ from the majority view?',
    answer: 'Khul\' (the wife\'s right to initiate divorce by returning the mahr or a financial equivalent to the husband) is one of the most important provisions protecting women\'s rights in Islamic family law. The Quranic foundation: ﴿فَإِنْ خِفْتُمْ أَلَّا يُقِيمَا حُدُودَ اللَّهِ فَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَيْهِمَا فِيمَا افْتَدَتْ بِهِ﴾ (Quran 2:229) — "If you fear that they will not maintain the limits of Allah, there is no blame on either of them for what she gives to free herself." The Sunnah precedent: the wife of Thabit ibn Qays came to the Prophet ﷺ saying she did not dislike Thabit\'s character or religion but feared disbelieving (kufr) due to hatred — the Prophet ﷺ said: "Will you return his garden?" She said yes. The Prophet ﷺ commanded Thabit to accept the garden and divorce her (Sahih Al-Bukhari 5273). Ibn Qudamah\'s analysis in Al-Mughni: the majority position across all four schools holds that Khul\' requires the husband\'s consent — it is a contractual dissolution requiring both parties\' agreement. The wife offers compensation, the husband accepts and divorces. Without the husband\'s consent, Khul\' cannot be effected even if the wife has genuine cause. The rationale: divorce is in the husband\'s hand (bi-yadih) — Islamic law gives him the right to initiate talaq, and Khul\' functions as a bilateral agreement to dissolve the marriage. Ibn Taymiyyah\'s position (supported by a group of Hanbali scholars): in cases where the wife has genuine harm or genuine inability to remain in the marriage, the judge can dissolve the marriage (faskh) without the husband\'s consent, either upon Khul\' terms or without compensation if the harm is attributable to the husband. His evidence: the case of Thabit\'s wife shows the Prophet ﷺ did not seek Thabit\'s consent first — he asked the wife about returning the garden, then commanded Thabit. Additionally, if the husband refuses Khul\' while the wife has genuine cause, allowing him to trap her in the marriage violates the Quranic command to "retain in goodness or release." This position has been adopted by several Muslim-majority countries\' personal status laws (notably Egypt\'s 2000 Khul\' law) as the basis for judicial Khul\' without husband consent.',
    source: 'Al-Mughni (Vol. 7), Ibn Qudamah; Majmoo\' Al-Fatawa (Vol. 32), Ibn Taymiyyah; Sahih Al-Bukhari 5273; Al-Muhalla (Vol. 10), Ibn Hazm; Ahkam Al-Khul\', various',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_35',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the classical analysis of Fiqh Al-Jihad in its comprehensive sense — how does Ibn Rushd\'s Bidayat Al-Mujtahid structure the question of offensive vs. defensive jihad, and what is Ibn Taymiyyah\'s doctrine of Jihad Al-Daf\' (defensive jihad) as an individual obligation when Muslim lands are invaded?',
    answer: 'The classical fiqh of Jihad encompasses multiple categories that are often conflated in contemporary discourse. Ibn Rushd Al-Andalusi (Averroes) in Bidayat Al-Mujtahid provides the most structurally clear classical analysis. He identifies the core scholarly controversies as: (1) Is offensive jihad (initiating military action against non-Muslim territories) a fard kifayah (communal obligation) or entirely optional? The majority position: fard kifayah — the Muslim community collectively is obligated to maintain military capacity and to expand the domain of justice (not necessarily Islamic governance) until the conditions of Quran 9:29 are met. Once sufficiently fulfilled by some, the obligation is lifted from others. (2) Under what conditions can non-combatants be targeted? The majority: never directly. Collateral damage rules parallel modern international humanitarian law principles. (3) The treatment of People of the Book vs. polytheists: the classical schools distinguish the options (jizyah, conversion, or sword) for different categories — Ibn Rushd surveys the disagreements without resolving them in a single formula. Ibn Taymiyyah\'s distinctive contribution — Jihad Al-Daf\' (defensive jihad): in his fatwa on fighting the Tatars (who had converted to Islam but continued to impose Mongol law), he develops the doctrine that defensive jihad is fard \'ayn (individual obligation) for every capable person in the invaded territory and its vicinity when: (a) Muslim lands are invaded; (b) the imam calls for defense; (c) the threat is actual, not merely potential. This individual obligation overrides even personal financial constraints — the Muslim must defend even without the imam\'s specific command if the invasion is actual. His most significant legal move: he rules that fighting the Tatars (nominal Muslims who govern by Yasa, Mongol customary law, rather than Shariah) is legitimate because they have replaced Islamic governance with non-Islamic law — their profession of Islam does not exempt them from fighting if they impose un-Islamic governance. This fatwa has been enormously influential and enormously contested — critics argue he creates a framework that can be used to justify fighting Muslim rulers indefinitely, while supporters argue he establishes principled grounds for resistance to oppression.',
    source: 'Bidayat Al-Mujtahid (Vol. 1), Ibn Rushd; Majmoo\' Al-Fatawa (Vol. 28), Ibn Taymiyyah; Al-Jihad fi Al-Islam, Sayyid Qutb (and classical critiques thereof); Al-Mughni (Jihad section), Ibn Qudamah; Al-Siyar Al-Kabir, Ash-Shaybani',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_36',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Analyze the classical doctrine of Al-Firaq (legal dissolution of marriage) — distinguish the five grounds for judicial dissolution (faskh) as enumerated in Maliki fiqh, and explain why the Maliki school is the most expansive in protecting wives from abusive or absent husbands.',
    answer: 'Faskh (judicial dissolution of marriage without husband\'s initiation) provides crucial protection for women in situations where the husband refuses to grant talaq but the marriage is genuinely harmful or functionally collapsed. The Maliki school has developed the most comprehensive grounds for faskh, reflecting Imam Malik\'s consistent attention to the rights of women within the marriage contract. The five major grounds in Maliki fiqh (as elaborated in Mawahib Al-Jalil and Al-Mudawwanah): (1) Darar (harm/injury) — any established pattern of physical harm, psychological abuse, persistent defamation, or sustained interference with the wife\'s rights. The Maliki standard for harm is the broadest: the judge evaluates whether a woman of similar status would consider this treatment harmful, and the bar is lower than requiring severe physical injury. The Shafi\'i school requires more serious documented harm. (2) Ghaybah (absence) — the husband\'s absence from the wife for an extended period without valid reason and without providing maintenance. The Maliki position: after one year of absence with no maintenance, the wife may petition for dissolution. The Hanafi school: the wife cannot seek faskh for mere absence — she must wait until his death is established. (3) \'Adam An-Nafaqah (failure of maintenance) — the husband\'s inability or refusal to provide the obligatory maintenance. Maliki: faskh is available after failure to provide maintenance for a defined period. Hanafi: inability to provide maintenance does not dissolve the marriage — the husband\'s debt to the wife continues and he may satisfy it when able. (4) \'Ilal (defects) — certain physical defects in the husband that prevent the marriage\'s objectives (sexual impotence, leprosy, severe mental illness). (5) Al-La\'n (li\'an oath) — after the husband accuses the wife of adultery and both make the li\'an oaths, the marriage is dissolved by the judge. The Maliki expansiveness reflects a fundamental principle: the marriage contract is bilateral and imposes obligations on both parties — when the husband systematically fails his obligations, the wife\'s option to exit must be protected.',
    source: 'Mawahib Al-Jalil, Al-Hattab; Al-Mudawwanah (Vol. 2), Sahnun; Al-Fiqh Al-Maliki fi Thawbihi Al-Jadid, Muhammad \'Alish; Al-Mughni (Kitab An-Nafaqat), Ibn Qudamah; Rawdat At-Talibin, An-Nawawi',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_37',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the position of the four schools on inheritance by non-Muslims from Muslim relatives — analyze the hadith "La yarith al-muslim al-kafir wa la al-kafir al-muslim" in light of the \'illah dispute, and what is Ibn Hazm\'s Zahiri challenge to this ruling?',
    answer: 'The prohibition on mutual inheritance between Muslims and non-Muslims is established by the Prophet\'s statement: "A Muslim does not inherit from a disbeliever, and a disbeliever does not inherit from a Muslim." (Sahih Al-Bukhari 6764, Sahih Muslim 1614 — transmitted by Usamah ibn Zayd.) The rule is bilateral: neither party inherits from the other. The scholarly consensus on this hadith is near-universal — it is Sahih, authenticated by all hadith masters, and represents one of the most clearly established rules in Islamic inheritance law. The four schools all accept the prohibition; their differences are in application to edge cases: (1) The murtadd (apostate): the apostate\'s status as an heir and an inherited-from is disputed. Hanafi: the apostate does not inherit from Muslims, but Muslims do inherit from the apostate — the apostate\'s wealth passes to their Muslim heirs upon death or execution. This asymmetry reflects the Hanafi view that apostasy does not immediately eliminate Muslim civil status until judgment. Maliki, Shafi\'i, Hanbali: the apostate inherits nothing from Muslims and Muslims inherit nothing from the apostate — their estate goes to the Muslim treasury (bayt al-mal) not Muslim heirs. (2) The dhimmi\'s relationship to a Muslim: no inheritance regardless of relationship closeness. Ibn Hazm\'s challenge in Al-Muhalla: his Zahiri methodology forces him to confront the hadith\'s literal scope. He accepts the hadith but argues its \'illah (effective cause) is kufr in the sense of open enmity (muharaba) — not mere theological disagreement. A dhimmi living under Islamic protection, fulfilling their covenant, who happens to be the child or parent of a Muslim, is not the target of this ruling because they are not a "kafir" in the militarily adversarial sense the hadith addresses. This argument has attracted attention but has not been accepted by any major school — the hadith is understood as addressing religious difference (din), not military status (muharaba). The contemporary relevance: in Muslim-minority contexts where Muslims marry and have children with non-Muslims, the prohibition creates complex inheritance situations that Fiqh Al-Aqalliyyat scholarship is still working through.',
    source: 'Sahih Al-Bukhari 6764; Fath Al-Bari (Vol. 12), Ibn Hajar; Al-Muhalla (Vol. 9), Ibn Hazm; Al-Mughni (Vol. 6), Ibn Qudamah; Ahkam Al-Mawarith, various',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_38',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Explain the principle of Al-Hukm Yudur ma\'a \'Illatihi Wujudan wa \'Adaman (the ruling follows the \'illah in its presence and absence) — how does this principle operate in the case of Zakah on \'Urud At-Tijarah (trade goods), where the \'illah is commercial intent, and what are the methodological consequences when the \'illah is internal and unverifiable?',
    answer: 'The legal maxim "Al-Hukm yudur ma\'a \'illatihi wujudan wa \'adaman" (the ruling revolves around its \'illah — present when it is present, absent when it is absent) is the core principle of qiyas and represents the most important methodological tool in Islamic legal extension. Its application to Zakah on \'Urud At-Tijarah (trade inventory goods) reveals both the power and the complexity of the principle when the \'illah is internal (niyyah — intention) rather than external and observable. The Zakah obligation on trade goods is established not by an explicit Quranic verse (unlike gold, silver, and agricultural produce) but by analogy: goods held for the purpose of trade (tijarah) are subject to Zakah at 2.5% of their value when one lunar year has passed, based on the hadith of Samurah ibn Jundub (Sunan Abu Dawud 1562 — the authenticity of which As-Sarakhsi discusses) and the practice of the Companions. The \'illah making goods subject to Zakah is qasdu at-tijarah (intent to trade) — the same goods held for personal use are not subject to Zakah. This creates the methodological challenge: the \'illah is the owner\'s internal intention, which cannot be directly observed. The consequences: (1) If someone buys goods with the explicit intent to use them, they are not subject to Zakah — even if they subsequently decide to sell them. The intent at time of purchase determines the ruling per the Hanafi-Shafi\'i majority position. (2) If someone inherits goods and then intends to sell them, Zakah applies from the date of that intention, not from the date of inheritance. (3) The Maliki qualification: commercial goods are subject to Zakah when they are actually traded — the intent alone is insufficient if the goods are held without active trading. This adds an objective behavioral element to the subjective intent-based \'illah. The deeper methodological point: when an \'illah is internal (like niyyah), the Shariah cannot enforce Zakah through direct observation but relies on self-declaration — highlighting the Islamic legal system\'s fundamental reliance on individual piety and accounting to Allah.',
    source: 'Usul As-Sarakhsi (Vol. 1); Al-Mabsut (Vol. 2), As-Sarakhsi; Al-Mughni (Kitab Az-Zakah), Ibn Qudamah; Fiqh Az-Zakah (Vol. 1), Al-Qaradawi; Rawdat At-Talibin, An-Nawawi',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_39',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the classical analysis of Bay\' Al-Murabahah (cost-plus sale) — how does As-Sarakhsi\'s Al-Mabsut establish its conditions, and what is the scholarly basis for the contemporary criticism that murabahah as practiced in Islamic banking is a hilah to legitimize interest-based lending?',
    answer: 'Bay\' Al-Murabahah (the cost-plus sale — selling goods at cost plus a disclosed profit margin) is one of the oldest and most analyzed sale types in classical Islamic commercial law. As-Sarakhsi\'s treatment in Al-Mabsut is comprehensive and establishes several conditions that distinguish a valid murabahah from a prohibited transaction: (1) The seller must have actually owned and possessed the goods — murabahah is a sale, not a loan, and the seller must have genuine ownership risk (dhaman) before selling. (2) The cost must be accurately disclosed — misrepresentation of cost makes the murabahah voidable and the misrepresenting party liable. (3) The profit must be a percentage of actual cost — not a disguised interest charge. (4) The goods must exist and be deliverable — no forward murabahah without salam conditions. Contemporary criticism: the Islamic banking product called "murabahah li-al-amir bil-shira\'" (murabahah to the purchase orderer) involves: (a) Client requests a specific commodity; (b) Bank purchases it; (c) Bank sells to client at cost-plus profit payable in installments. Critics including Muhammad Taqi Usmani, Sami Homoud, and OIC Fiqh Academy scholars identify the following concerns: (1) If the bank purchases only after the client\'s binding promise (wa\'d mulzim), it never genuinely bears risk — it is purchasing to order, not trading. Classical scholars like Ibn Taymiyyah prohibit "Buy it for me and I will buy it from you" precisely because this eliminates the seller\'s risk. (2) If the installment payment in murabahah is indexed to the time period (longer term = higher cost), the cost-plus structure is functionally equivalent to interest — the money value of time is incorporated. (3) If the bank never actually takes physical possession — merely processing paperwork — the ownership is fictional. The primary counter-argument: genuine ownership risk (dhaman) exists even briefly, distinguishing it from riba; and the fixed cost-plus structure, unlike interest, does not compound or float with market rates, creating a materially different risk profile.',
    source: 'Al-Mabsut (Vol. 13), As-Sarakhsi; Bay\' Al-Murabahah, Muhammad Taqi Usmani; OIC Fiqh Academy Resolution; Murabahah to the Purchase Orderer, AAOIFI Standard 2; Bai\' Bi-Thaman Ajil, Bank Negara Malaysia',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_40',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Analyze the classical doctrine of Al-Ihsam (judicial confirmation of marriage contracts) and the Maliki institution of the Qadi\'s role as Wali (marriage guardian) for women without guardians — how does Al-Mudawwanah present Malik\'s position that the Qadi\'s wilayah is genuine, not merely procedural?',
    answer: 'The Maliki institution of the Qadi as Wali (marriage guardian) for women without natural guardians (Sultan Waliyyu Man La Waliyya Lah — "the ruler is the guardian of whoever has no guardian") is among the most practically significant jurisprudential positions affecting Muslim women\'s rights in minority contexts and in situations where the natural guardian refuses or is absent. The Prophetic foundation: "The Sultan (ruler/judge) is the guardian of whoever has no guardian." (Sunan Abu Dawud 2083, authenticated.) Al-Mudawwanah Al-Kubra records Malik\'s position with characteristic specificity. Ibn Al-Qasim transmits: "Malik said: If a woman has no wali (guardian), the Sultan marries her. If she is in a land where there is no Sultan, the honest men of her community marry her." This last clause is uniquely Maliki — in the absence of formal judicial authority, community elders can serve the guardian function, preventing women from being permanently unable to marry due to institutional unavailability. The distinction between Maliki and Shafi\'i-Hanbali positions: All schools agree the Qadi can serve as wali for a woman with no surviving male agnate relatives (no father, grandfather, brothers, paternal uncles). The Shafi\'i and Hanbali schools: the Qadi\'s wilayah is procedural — he performs the guardian\'s function but the authority is delegated from the state\'s power of guardianship by succession of authority. The Maliki position per Al-Mudawwanah: the Qadi\'s wilayah is genuine — he stands in the position of wali with full independent authority to evaluate the compatibility of the marriage, the adequacy of the mahr, and the suitability of the husband, exactly as a natural wali would. He is not merely completing a formality but exercising substantive protective judgment. This distinction matters practically: the Maliki Qadi can refuse a marriage on grounds that a procedural-guardian would not have standing to raise, and can insist on conditions that protect the woman\'s interests in ways a purely procedural authority cannot.',
    source: 'Al-Mudawwanah Al-Kubra (Vol. 2), Sahnun; Al-Muwatta (Kitab An-Nikah), Imam Malik; Mawahib Al-Jalil, Al-Hattab; Al-Mughni (Vol. 7), Ibn Qudamah; Rawdat At-Talibin (Vol. 7), An-Nawawi',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_41',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the Hanafi doctrine of Mal Al-Mustaghall (invested/productive property) and how does it affect the Nisab calculation for Zakah — explain As-Sarakhsi\'s position that intermediate income (income during the Zakah year) becomes Zakatable along with the original Nisab even if it did not exist at the beginning of the year.',
    answer: 'The question of how Zakah applies to income, returns, and newly acquired assets during the Zakah year is one of the most practically complex in contemporary Zakah jurisprudence, and the classical schools differ substantially. As-Sarakhsi\'s treatment in Al-Mabsut establishes the specifically Hanafi doctrine of Namaʾ Al-Mal (growth of wealth) and its Zakah implications. The Hanafi position: wealth that grows from an existing Nisab — whether through profit, birth (in the case of livestock), or new acquisition of the same type — is subject to Zakah along with the original Nisab at the end of the Zakah year, even if the new wealth was acquired during the year. The rationale: the new wealth has "grown from" (nashi\' min) the original Zakatable wealth and is therefore subject to the same ruling by the principle of Ilhaq (appending). Example: A person has 100 gold units (above Nisab) on 1 Muharram. By 30 Dhul-Hijjah, through trading, they have 200 gold units. All 200 units are Zakatable, even though 100 units were acquired during the year and did not complete a full Hawl (lunar year). The Shafi\'i and Hanbali position: only wealth present at both the beginning and end of the Hawl is Zakatable from that year\'s perspective. New wealth acquired during the year begins its own separate Hawl from the date of acquisition. As-Sarakhsi\'s methodological point: this distinction has enormous practical consequences. Under the Hanafi rule, a trader who begins the year with Nisab and actively trades need only calculate Zakah once per year on all accumulated wealth. Under the Shafi\'i-Hanbali rule, a very active trader might theoretically need to calculate Zakah on multiple pools of wealth each with their own Hawl — a practically impossible burden that the Hanafi rule sensibly avoids. The Maliki position is intermediate: Zakah is due on newly acquired wealth of the same type as the original Nisab, but requires genuine temporal connection — the new wealth must have been acquired through the original wealth\'s activity, not independently.',
    source: 'Al-Mabsut (Vol. 2), As-Sarakhsi; Al-Mughni (Kitab Az-Zakah), Ibn Qudamah; Fiqh Az-Zakah (Vol. 1), Al-Qaradawi; Al-Majmu\' (Kitab Az-Zakah), An-Nawawi; Al-Mudawwanah (Kitab Az-Zakah), Sahnun',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_42',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Explain the doctrine of Tabdil An-Niyyah (change of intention) in Islamic contract law — when does a change of intention change the legal ruling of an act, and how does the principle interact with the Hanafi concept that contracts are governed by their explicit terms (Sigha) rather than the parties\' hidden intentions?',
    answer: 'The relationship between Niyyah (intention) and legal ruling in Islamic contract law reveals a fundamental tension: the Prophetic principle "Actions are by intentions" (Sahih Al-Bukhari 1) suggests that the ruling follows intention, while basic contract theory requires that agreements be enforceable based on their explicit terms (sigha — offer and acceptance), not on hidden intentions. The Hanafi resolution is the most sophisticated. As-Sarakhsi in Al-Mabsut distinguishes two categories: (1) Acts of worship (\'Ibadat): intention is determinative. The same physical act (washing hands) has different legal effects depending on whether it was performed with the intention of wudu, ghusl, or merely hygiene. The sigha (spoken words or physical act) cannot substitute for intention in \'ibadat. (2) Contracts and transactions (Mu\'amalat): the explicit sigha (terms of the contract) governs, and hidden intentions generally cannot modify the legal effect. If A sells B a house in a valid contract, A cannot unilaterally "intend" the sale as a gift and thereby modify the contract. However — the Hanafi exception — when the evidence of hidden intention is externally verifiable, it can affect the ruling. The primary application: Nikah contracted with the intention of Mut\'ah (temporary marriage) is invalid in Sunni law not because of the unspoken intention but because courts can reasonably infer the intention from context. The Tabdil An-Niyyah (change of intention) doctrine: if someone purchases a commodity intending to use it personally, then later intends to sell it for profit, does this change of intention start a new Hawl for Zakah purposes? As-Sarakhsi: yes — the change of intention from personal use to trade is legally effective because intention is the \'illah of Zakah on trade goods. Conversely, if someone purchases trade goods and then intends to keep them personally, the Zakah obligation ceases. The underlying principle: in \'ibadat and in acts whose ruling depends specifically on internal intention, Tabdil An-Niyyah changes the ruling. In bilateral contracts and acts governed by external sigha, it does not.',
    source: 'Al-Mabsut (Vol. 2-3), As-Sarakhsi; Usul As-Sarakhsi; Al-Badai\' As-Sanai\', Al-Kasani; Al-Majmu\' (Vol. 6), An-Nawawi; Qa\'idat Al-Umur bi-Maqasidiha, various',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_43',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the classical theory of Al-Qada\' wa Al-Qadar (divine decree and human will) as it relates to Islamic jurisprudence — how does Ibn Al-Qayyim\'s Shifa\' Al-\'Alil address the compatibility between determinism and legal responsibility, and what are the practical implications for the fiqh of \'Adhab (punishment)?',
    answer: 'The relationship between divine decree (Qadar) and human legal responsibility (Taklif) is one of theology\'s deepest problems and has direct implications for Islamic jurisprudence — specifically for the basis of punishment, the nature of legal capacity, and the theological coherence of obligation. Ibn Al-Qayyim\'s Shifa\' Al-\'Alil fi Masa\'il Al-Qada\' wa Al-Qadar wa Al-Hikmah wa At-Ta\'lil is the most extensive classical treatment of this question from the Hanbali-Athari perspective. His core thesis against the Jabriyyah (complete determinists who deny meaningful human agency): the existence of divine decree does not eliminate the reality of human choice, because: (1) Humans experience the reality of their own will — the distinction between a voluntary action and compelled action is self-evident experientially. (2) The Quran itself addresses humans as choosing agents who will be held accountable: ﴿فَمَن شَاءَ فَلْيُؤْمِن وَمَن شَاءَ فَلْيَكْفُرْ﴾ (Quran 18:29). (3) The argument from divine justice: Allah\'s punishment of those who disobey is just only if they genuinely could have chosen otherwise — a purely determined universe would make divine punishment unjust. Ibn Al-Qayyim\'s against the Mu\'tazilah (who assert complete human self-determination independent of divine will): the Quran is explicit that Allah wills everything that happens, including human choices, without this eliminating human responsibility. The Sunni (Ash\'ari-Athari) position: Kasb (acquisition) — humans perform acts through a divinely created capacity, but their acquisition of the act creates genuine responsibility. Ibn Al-Qayyim\'s distinctively Hanbali addition: the compatibility of divine will and human responsibility is ultimately a divine mystery — "We know the conclusion from revelation: humans are responsible; divine decree encompasses everything. How these are compatible is above full human comprehension." Practical implications for fiqh: (1) The legal system holds people responsible because they experience themselves as choosing — regardless of the theological question of determinism. (2) Diminished responsibility (ikrah — compulsion) reduces legal liability when choice is externally constrained, not merely because of theological determinism. (3) The concept of \'Udhr (excuse) in fiqh tracks external constraints on choice, not internal theological puzzles about free will.',
    source: 'Shifa\' Al-\'Alil, Ibn Al-Qayyim; Majmoo\' Al-Fatawa (Vol. 8), Ibn Taymiyyah; Al-Aqidah Al-Wasitiyyah, Ibn Taymiyyah; Lum\'at Al-I\'tiqad, Ibn Qudamah; Al-Kasb, Al-Ash\'ari',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_44',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Analyze the Quranic principle of \'Adl (justice) in Ibn \'Ashur\'s Maqasid framework — how does he argue that \'Adl is itself a primary Maqsad independent of the classical five, and what is the methodological basis for his expansion of Maqasid theory beyond Al-Ghazali?',
    answer: 'Muhammad Tahir Ibn \'Ashur\'s Maqasid Ash-Shariah Al-Islamiyyah (1946) represents the most significant development of Maqasid theory in the twentieth century and arguably the most important contribution to Islamic legal philosophy since Ash-Shatibi. His primary methodological innovation: the classical five Maqasid (din, nafs, nasl, \'aql, mal) are not incorrect but are incomplete. They were derived by induction from the fiqh tradition as Al-Ghazali and Ash-Shatibi practiced it — but if one induces from the totality of Islamic social teachings, Quranic ethical principles, and Prophetic guidance (not merely from the fiqh of worship and transactions), additional primary Maqasid emerge. Ibn \'Ashur\'s additional Maqasid: (1) Al-Fitrah (natural human constitution) — the Shariah works with, not against, the natural dispositions Allah built into humanity. ﴿فَأَقِمْ وَجْهَكَ لِلدِّينِ حَنِيفاً فِطْرَتَ اللَّهِ الَّتِي فَطَرَ النَّاسَ عَلَيْهَا﴾ (Quran 30:30). (2) Al-Musawah (equality) — the fundamental human equality proclaimed in Islam has legal implications for how rights and obligations are distributed. (3) Al-Hurriyyah (freedom) — Islamic law protects human freedom as a basic value, not merely as instrumental to the five classical Maqasid. (4) \'Adl (justice) — Justice is a primary Maqsad in its own right, not merely a consequence of protecting the five. The Quran commands \'adl repeatedly: ﴿إِنَّ اللَّهَ يَأْمُرُ بِالْعَدْلِ وَالْإِحْسَانِ﴾ (Quran 16:90). Methodological basis for expansion: Ibn \'Ashur argues that Ash-Shatibi\'s inductive method — examining the full body of Islamic teaching — must be applied to the social, political, and international dimensions of Islamic teaching, not merely to fiqh al-fard (individual obligation law). When this expanded induction is performed, the Maqasid must be expanded accordingly. Critical response from traditionalists: expanding the Maqasid risks losing the analytical precision that makes them useful as legal tools — if every Quranic value becomes a Maqsad, the framework loses its ability to distinguish between primary and secondary considerations.',
    source: 'Maqasid Ash-Shariah Al-Islamiyyah, Ibn \'Ashur; Al-Muwafaqat, Ash-Shatibi; Dirasat fi Falsafat Tashri\' Al-Islami, Al-Raysouni; Nazariyyat Al-Maqasid \'Ind Al-Imam Ibn \'Ashur, Ismail Al-Hasani',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_45',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Explain the Maliki doctrine of \'Amal Ahl Al-Madinah (the practice of the people of Madinah) — how does Imam Malik in Al-Muwatta use it as a superior evidence to individual hadith reports, and what is Ash-Shafi\'i\'s systematic critique in Ar-Risalah?',
    answer: '\'Amal Ahl Al-Madinah (the practice of the people of Madinah) is Imam Malik\'s most distinctive methodological principle and the most controversial. In Al-Muwatta, Malik repeatedly cites "the practice that has continued among us" as evidence stronger than individual hadith reports — including, in famous instances, stronger than hadiths transmitted in Sahih Muslim. The theological basis: Madinah was the city of the Prophet ﷺ — the community that witnessed the Prophet\'s practice directly, was trained by him personally, and transmitted his practice continuously through lived community behavior (tawatur \'amali — continuous practical transmission) rather than through verbal narration chains subject to individual memory errors. In Malik\'s epistemology: the community\'s continuous practice is stronger evidence of what the Prophet ﷺ actually did than any individual verbal narration, because the community cannot collectively err in preserving practices that occurred in their midst. Examples: (1) The practice of not reciting Bismillah audibly before Al-Fatihah in prayer — contradicting several hadiths suggesting audible recitation — is established for Malik by Madinan practice. (2) The raf\' al-yadayn (raising hands in prayer) debate: Malik\'s position tracks Madinan practice, not the strong hadith evidence supporting extensive hand-raising. (3) The Adhan details — specific words and repetitions — are established by Madinan practice over individual reports of other formulations. Ash-Shafi\'i\'s systematic critique in Ar-Risalah (and Jimma\' Al-\'Ilm): (1) \'Amal is performed by individuals within the community — community practice can only be legally authoritative if it constitutes genuine Ijma\' (consensus), which requires that all scholars of the era explicitly agree. (2) If Madinan practice contradicts an authentic verbal hadith, the hadith is specific Sunnah while the practice may reflect an individual scholar\'s ijtihad that has become customary — the Sunnah overrides it. (3) There is no special status for Madinah after the Prophet\'s death — the Prophet\'s companions dispersed across the world, and Kufan, Syrian, and Egyptian practices have the same theoretical authority as Madinan practice if they represent transmission from the same Companions.',
    source: 'Al-Muwatta, Imam Malik; Ar-Risalah, Ash-Shafi\'i; Jimma\' Al-\'Ilm, Ash-Shafi\'i; Al-Istidhkar, Ibn \'Abd Al-Barr; Tarikh Al-Fiqh Al-Islami, Muhammad Al-Khudhri',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_46',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the doctrine of Tanaqud Al-Adillah (conflict of evidences) in Usul Al-Fiqh — trace the full hierarchy of conflict resolution (Jam\', Tarjih, Naskh, Tawaqquf) as established by Al-Amidi in Al-Ihkam, and explain why Ash-Shatibi argues that genuine irresolvable conflict between primary sources is impossible.',
    answer: 'Tanaqud Al-Adillah (apparent conflict between evidences) is addressed by the most advanced Usul methodology, and its resolution process reveals the deepest assumptions of Islamic legal epistemology. Al-Amidi\'s Al-Ihkam fi Usul Al-Ahkam provides the most systematic classical treatment. His four-stage hierarchy: (1) Al-Jam\' wa At-Tawfiq (reconciliation) — the preferred response whenever possible. If two evidences appear to conflict, the first task is to examine whether they actually address the same situation or can be applied in different contexts without genuine conflict. Example: "If something is made wudu from, it may be prayed with" appears to conflict with "Wudu made from a dead animal\'s skin is not valid" — reconciled by distinguishing tanned vs. untanned skin. (2) At-Tarjih (preference of one over another) — when reconciliation is impossible, the stronger evidence prevails through criteria of: chain strength (Isnad), textual explicitness (Nass vs. Zahir), compatibility with other established principles, logical consistency, and number of supporting evidences. (3) An-Naskh (abrogation) — when reconciliation and preference both fail and the chronological sequence is known, the later evidence abrogates the earlier. Requires proof of chronological priority — not merely assertion. (4) At-Tawaqquf (suspension) — when all three preceding methods fail, the jurist suspends judgment, declares the question unresolvable, and typically defaults to the principle of permissibility (Ibahah) or the prior known ruling. Ash-Shatibi\'s radical claim in Al-Muwafaqat: genuine irresolvable conflict between Quranic verses, or between a Quranic verse and a mutawatir hadith, is impossible. The Quran is internally consistent (﴿وَلَوْ كَانَ مِنْ عِندِ غَيْرِ اللَّهِ لَوَجَدُوا فِيهِ اخْتِلَافاً كَثِيراً﴾ — Quran 4:82) and cannot genuinely contradict itself. Apparent conflicts always reflect inadequate understanding on the part of the jurist — either in the meaning of the text, the application of context, or the identification of the \'illah. This is not a naive claim but a methodological commitment: the jurist must keep searching for reconciliation rather than accepting conflict, because accepting irreducible conflict would undermine the Quran\'s character as divine revelation.',
    source: 'Al-Ihkam fi Usul Al-Ahkam, Al-Amidi; Al-Muwafaqat, Ash-Shatibi; Ar-Risalah, Ash-Shafi\'i; Rawdat An-Nazir, Ibn Qudamah; Al-Mustasfa, Al-Ghazali',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_47',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Analyze the classical debate on the Hanafi concept of \'Urf Al-\'Amal (customary practice in commercial transactions) as a source of law — how does Al-Kasani\'s Al-Badai\' As-Sanai\' use \'urf to validate contracts not explicitly endorsed by the foundational texts, and what are the limits of this validation?',
    answer: 'Al-Kasani\'s Al-Badai\' As-Sanai\' fi Tartib Ash-Shara\'i\' is among the finest works of Hanafi fiqh and develops the role of \'Urf (custom) most extensively in the context of commercial law. Al-Kasani\'s methodological position: \'Urf Al-\'Amal (customary commercial practice) that is widespread, continuous, and not opposed to any explicit text has legal authority to validate contracts, modify default terms, and establish obligations that a strict textual reading would not support. His foundational principle: "What is established by \'urf is as if established by nass" (Ma thabata bil-\'urf ka-ma thabata bin-nass) — a maxim that appears in Al-Badai\' and becomes a standard legal maxim. Applications in Al-Badai\': (1) Istisna\' (manufacturing contracts): validated primarily by \'urf — "The Muslims have continued to commission craftsmen throughout the ages without objection, and this constitutes continuous established practice." No specific text validates Istisna\'; \'urf does. (2) Mu\'atah (exchange without verbal offer and acceptance): in markets where prices are posted and buyers select goods without verbal negotiation, the exchange is valid by \'urf even though classical contract theory requires explicit Ijab and Qabul. (3) Bay\' Al-Mu\'atah: validated in most goods by \'urf, though the Shafi\'i school requires verbal Ijab/Qabul. (4) Modern banking instruments: contemporary Hanafi scholars extend this to validate new financial instruments whose specific structures are not mentioned in classical texts but reflect universal commercial practice. The limits of \'urf validation: (1) \'Urf cannot validate what a specific text prohibits — riba is prohibited by Quranic text; no level of commercial custom can validate it. (2) \'Urf must be genuine custom — universal and continuous — not merely majority practice in a particular time and place. (3) \'Urf Al-Fasid (corrupt custom) — custom that contradicts the purposes of the Shariah even without opposing a specific text — has no authority.',
    source: 'Al-Badai\' As-Sanai\' (Vol. 5-6), Al-Kasani; Al-Mabsut (Vol. 12), As-Sarakhsi; Al-Ashbah wa An-Naza\'ir, Ibn Nujaym; Al-Majallah Al-\'Adliyyah (Ottoman Civil Code); Fiqh Al-\'Urf, Mukhtar Ahmad Nadwi',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_48',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the classical doctrine of Al-Mashaqqah Tajlib At-Taysir (hardship brings about ease) — how does Ash-Shatibi in Al-Muwafaqat distinguish between genuine Mashaqqah that activates legal concessions and ordinary inconvenience that does not, and what are the six categories of recognized hardship?',
    answer: 'The legal maxim "Al-Mashaqqah Tajlib At-Taysir" (hardship brings about ease) is one of the five major maxims of Islamic law, grounded in multiple Quranic verses: ﴿يُرِيدُ اللَّهُ بِكُمُ الْيُسْرَ وَلَا يُرِيدُ بِكُمُ الْعُسْرَ﴾ (Quran 2:185) and ﴿وَمَا جَعَلَ عَلَيْكُمْ فِي الدِّينِ مِنْ حَرَجٍ﴾ (Quran 22:78). The deepest treatment is in Ash-Shatibi\'s Al-Muwafaqat (Vol. 2, the section on Rukhsah and \'Azimah). His critical distinction: not every difficulty qualifies as the Mashaqqah that activates legal concessions. The test is not subjective — it is not "does this person find this difficult?" but rather "does this difficulty rise to the level that the Shariah recognizes as activating concession?" Ash-Shatibi\'s criteria for legally recognized hardship: (1) The hardship must be of a type recognized by the Shariah as activating concessions — the six recognized categories (asbab at-takhfif): As-Safar (travel), Al-Marad (illness), Al-Ikrah (coercion), An-Naqsul Ahlliyyah (diminished capacity — childhood, insanity), An-Nisyan (forgetfulness), \'Umum Al-Balwa (widespread unavoidable circumstance). (2) The hardship must be above the ordinary level that all religious obligation imposes — prayer requires effort; that effort is not Mashaqqah. The Mashaqqah that activates concessions is hardship substantially above the ordinary burden of the obligation. (3) The hardship must be actual, not merely feared — hypothetical future difficulty does not activate concessions. Ash-Shatibi\'s most important warning: the principle of ease (taysir) does not mean Islam seeks to minimize obligations. The principle means that where genuine hardship would make an obligation impossible to fulfill in its standard form, an alternative form is available that fulfills the same maqsad with less hardship. The purpose is never elimination of the obligation but preservation of the maqsad while acknowledging human limitations. This warning directly addresses the modern tendency to invoke "hardship" to justify wholesale abandonment of obligations.',
    source: 'Al-Muwafaqat (Vol. 1-2), Ash-Shatibi; Al-Ashbah wa An-Naza\'ir, As-Suyuti; Qawa\'id Al-Ahkam, Ibn \'Abd As-Salam; Al-Majmu\' (Vol. 1), An-Nawawi; Majallat Al-Ahkam Al-\'Adliyyah',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_49',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'What is the classical treatment of Ahl Al-Fatrah (people who lived between prophets without receiving revealed guidance) — how do Ibn Taymiyyah and Ibn Al-Qayyim\'s positions in Tariq Al-Hijratayn differ from the dominant Ash\'ari position, and what are the fiqhi implications for understanding the scope of \'Udhr bil-Jahl (excuse of ignorance)?',
    answer: 'Ahl Al-Fatrah (people of the interval — those who lived between prophets or without access to revelation) present one of Islamic theology\'s deepest justice-problems: what is the fate of those who never received the message? The dominant Ash\'ari position (followed by An-Nawawi, Al-Ghazali, and most classical scholars): such people are subjected to a specific divine test on the Day of Judgment — they are not automatically pardoned nor automatically punished, but Allah tests them in a manner befitting their situation. The Quranic basis: ﴿وَمَا كُنَّا مُعَذِّبِينَ حَتَّىٰ نَبْعَثَ رَسُولاً﴾ (Quran 17:15) — "We never punish until We have sent a messenger." This verse is the foundation: those who genuinely never received a messenger are not punished before their status is determined. The majority Ash\'ari interpretation: they will be judged according to the fitrah (natural disposition) they were given — their worship of Allah through pure reason, their treatment of their fellow humans. Ibn Taymiyyah and Ibn Al-Qayyim\'s distinct position in Tariq Al-Hijratayn wa Bab As-Sa\'adatayn: they argue that Ahl Al-Fatrah who followed the fitrah faithfully and worshipped Allah sincerely to the best of their knowledge are among the people of Paradise — the verse "We never punish until We have sent a messenger" is not merely procedural but substantive. Punishment requires hujjah (established proof) — those without access to hujjah cannot be punished. This is a stronger statement of divine justice: not "they will be tested" but "without hujjah there is no \'adhab." The fiqhi implications for \'Udhr bil-Jahl (excuse of ignorance): Ibn Taymiyyah consistently argues that Jahl (ignorance) of a ruling excuses from punishment — both in this world (no hadd applied where knowledge is genuinely absent) and in the next. This has direct implications for new Muslims who violated Islamic law before conversion, for Muslims in isolated communities without access to Islamic education, and for the scope of takfir (declaring someone outside Islam) — Ibn Taymiyyah requires that the hujjah (evidence, argument) be established against a specific person before takfir.',
    source: 'Tariq Al-Hijratayn, Ibn Al-Qayyim; Majmoo\' Al-Fatawa (Vol. 15), Ibn Taymiyyah; Al-Majmu\' (Vol. 1), An-Nawawi; Shifa\' Al-\'Alil, Ibn Al-Qayyim; Al-Jawab As-Sahih, Ibn Taymiyyah',
  },
  {
    id: 'fiqh_adv_50',
    level: 'advanced',
    discipline: 'fiqh',
    question: 'Synthesize the major methodological differences between the four Sunni madhabs as schools of jurisprudence (not merely as sets of rulings) — what does each school\'s usul methodology reveal about its foundational epistemological commitments, and why did Imam Ash-Shafi\'i consider the systematization of usul the prerequisite for all valid ijtihad?',
    answer: 'Understanding the four madhabs as methodological schools rather than rule-sets reveals that their disagreements are epistemological as much as substantive — they differ on what counts as evidence, how evidence is ranked, and what reasoning processes can be applied to evidence. The Hanafi School (Usul As-Sarakhsi, Kashf Al-Asrar Al-Bazdawi): founded on the Kufan ra\'y tradition, the Hanafi school uses systematic rational elaboration of legal principles derived from texts. Its epistemological commitment: legal reasoning is productive — from the texts plus principles, the jurist can construct rulings not explicitly stated. This enables Istihsan, \'Urf as primary evidence, and graduated application of general principles. Risk: rational elaboration may drift from textual grounding. The Maliki School (Al-Muwatta, Bidayat Al-Mujtahid): founded on Madinan practice as living Sunnah, the Maliki school\'s distinctive epistemological claim is that community practice can transmit Prophetic example more reliably than individual verbal narrations. Its commitment: continuity of community practice is itself a form of tawatur. Enables \'Amal Ahl Al-Madinah, Masalih Mursalah, and Sadd Dhara\'i\'. Risk: community practice may reflect later consensus-building rather than authentic Prophetic origin. The Shafi\'i School (Ar-Risalah, Al-Umm): Ash-Shafi\'i\'s revolution was the insistence that all valid legal reasoning must be anchored in explicit texts and that the methodology of anchoring must itself be systematized. His epistemological commitment: valid Islamic law is knowable only through the four established sources applied through transparent methodology — anything else is opinion, not Shariah. Enables methodological accountability. Risk: may undervalue contextual wisdom that resists textual systematization. The Hanbali School (Rawdat An-Nazir, Usul Al-Fiqh by Ibn Qudamah): rooted in Imam Ahmad\'s profound respect for hadith and distrust of independent rational elaboration. Its epistemological commitment: when texts speak, they must be followed without rational filtration; when texts are silent, caution and restriction are preferred over elaboration. Enables textual literalism and strong resistance to innovation. Risk: may apply texts rigidly without contextual sensitivity. Ash-Shafi\'i\'s prerequisite claim: "Whoever engages in fiqh without having mastered usul is like a person who builds on sand" — without a transparent methodology for deriving rulings, the jurist cannot be accountable to anything beyond their own opinion. The history of all four schools validates this: where their usul methodology is explicit, the rulings are arguable and revisable; where rulings have drifted from usul accountability, they become mere imitation (taqlid) without intellectual justification.',
    source: 'Ar-Risalah, Ash-Shafi\'i; Usul As-Sarakhsi; Rawdat An-Nazir, Ibn Qudamah; Al-Muwatta (Introduction), Imam Malik; Tarikh Al-Fiqh Al-Islami, Khudhri Bik; Al-Madhahib Al-Fiqhiyyah Al-Arba\'ah, Mahmud Al-Qabbani',
  },
]

