    answer: 'Pre-Islamic Makkah was governed not by a centralized state but by a complex system of tribal honor, economic power, and inter-clan alliances. The Quraysh tribe dominated through its control of the Haram and the pilgrimage trade — but this control was distributed among several powerful clans: Banu Makhzum (the dominant military clan), Banu Abd Shams (the wealthiest merchant clan, ancestor of the Umayyads), Banu Hashim (the Prophet\'s clan, prestigious but less wealthy), and Banu Abd Ad-Dar (custodians of specific Haram honors). The Hilf Al-Fudul (Confederation of the Virtuous) arose around 590 CE from a specific incident: a Yemeni merchant from the Zabid tribe sold goods to a Makhzumi nobleman who refused to pay. The merchant appealed publicly from Jabal Abu Qubays, and several clans responded — Banu Hashim, Banu Muttalib, Banu Asad, Banu Zuhrah, and Banu Taym convened at the house of Abdullah ibn Jud\'an (Taym clan) and swore to collectively protect the rights of wronged strangers in Makkah. The young Muhammad صلى الله عليه وسلم participated as a member of Banu Hashim. His later statement about it (recorded in As-Sirah An-Nabawiyyah of Ibn Hisham and Ibn Ishaq): "I witnessed in the house of Abdullah ibn Jud\'an a confederation that was more beloved to me than the most precious possessions — if I were called to it now in Islam, I would respond." This statement is jurisprudentially significant for several reasons. First, it establishes that the Prophet صلى الله عليه وسلم retroactively validated a pre-Islamic moral commitment — suggesting Islam does not require the total erasure of pre-Islamic virtue (al-khair al-jahili). Second, it demonstrates that protecting the weak and honoring contracts are moral universals that Islam affirms rather than innovations it introduces. Third, it provides the basis for Ibn Taymiyyah\'s jurisprudential argument that international agreements protecting human rights (even between Muslim and non-Muslim parties) are validatable within the Islamic legal framework — the Hilf Al-Fudul being the Prophetic precedent. The pre-Islamic period produced both jahiliyyah (the specific vices the Prophet صلى الله عليه وسلم came to abolish) and moral traditions the Prophet صلى الله عليه وسلم explicitly honored.',
